43/* The various kinds of conversion. */
44
45enum conversion_kind {
46 ck_identity,
47 ck_lvalue,
48 ck_fnptr,
49 ck_qual,
50 ck_std,
51 ck_ptr,
52 ck_pmem,
53 ck_base,
54 ck_ref_bind,
55 ck_user,
56 ck_ambig,
57 ck_list,
58 ck_aggr,
59 ck_rvalue
60};
61
62/* The rank of the conversion. Order of the enumerals matters; better
63 conversions should come earlier in the list. */
64
65enum conversion_rank {
66 cr_identity,
67 cr_exact,
68 cr_promotion,
69 cr_std,
70 cr_pbool,
71 cr_user,
72 cr_ellipsis,
73 cr_bad
74};
75
76/* An implicit conversion sequence, in the sense of [over.best.ics].
77 The first conversion to be performed is at the end of the chain.
78 That conversion is always a cr_identity conversion. */
79
80struct conversion {
81 /* The kind of conversion represented by this step. */
82 conversion_kind kind;
83 /* The rank of this conversion. */
84 conversion_rank rank;
85 BOOL_BITFIELD user_conv_p : 1;
86 BOOL_BITFIELD ellipsis_p : 1;
87 BOOL_BITFIELD this_p : 1;
88 /* True if this conversion would be permitted with a bending of
89 language standards, e.g. disregarding pointer qualifiers or
90 converting integers to pointers. */
91 BOOL_BITFIELD bad_p : 1;
92 /* If KIND is ck_ref_bind ck_base_conv, true to indicate that a
93 temporary should be created to hold the result of the
94 conversion. */
95 BOOL_BITFIELD need_temporary_p : 1;
96 /* If KIND is ck_ptr or ck_pmem, true to indicate that a conversion
97 from a pointer-to-derived to pointer-to-base is being performed. */
98 BOOL_BITFIELD base_p : 1;
99 /* If KIND is ck_ref_bind, true when either an lvalue reference is
100 being bound to an lvalue expression or an rvalue reference is
101 being bound to an rvalue expression. If KIND is ck_rvalue,
102 true when we should treat an lvalue as an rvalue (12.8p33). If
103 KIND is ck_base, always false. */
104 BOOL_BITFIELD rvaluedness_matches_p: 1;
105 BOOL_BITFIELD check_narrowing: 1;
106 /* The type of the expression resulting from the conversion. */
107 tree type;
108 union {
109 /* The next conversion in the chain. Since the conversions are
110 arranged from outermost to innermost, the NEXT conversion will
111 actually be performed before this conversion. This variant is
112 used only when KIND is neither ck_identity, ck_ambig nor
113 ck_list. Please use the next_conversion function instead
114 of using this field directly. */
115 conversion *next;
116 /* The expression at the beginning of the conversion chain. This
117 variant is used only if KIND is ck_identity or ck_ambig. */
118 tree expr;
119 /* The array of conversions for an initializer_list, so this
120 variant is used only when KIN D is ck_list. */
121 conversion **list;
122 } u;
123 /* The function candidate corresponding to this conversion
124 sequence. This field is only used if KIND is ck_user. */
125 struct z_candidate *cand;
126};
127
128#define CONVERSION_RANK(NODE) \
129 ((NODE)->bad_p ? cr_bad \
130 : (NODE)->ellipsis_p ? cr_ellipsis \
131 : (NODE)->user_conv_p ? cr_user \
132 : (NODE)->rank)
133
134#define BAD_CONVERSION_RANK(NODE) \
135 ((NODE)->ellipsis_p ? cr_ellipsis \
136 : (NODE)->user_conv_p ? cr_user \
137 : (NODE)->rank)
138

217/* Returns nonzero iff the destructor name specified in NAME matches BASETYPE.
218 NAME can take many forms... */
219
220bool
221check_dtor_name (tree basetype, tree name)
222{
223 /* Just accept something we've already complained about. */
224 if (name == error_mark_node)
225 return true;
226
227 if (TREE_CODE (name) == TYPE_DECL)
228 name = TREE_TYPE (name);
229 else if (TYPE_P (name))
230 /* OK */;
231 else if (identifier_p (name))
232 {
233 if ((MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (basetype)
234 && name == constructor_name (basetype))
235 || (TREE_CODE (basetype) == ENUMERAL_TYPE
236 && name == TYPE_IDENTIFIER (basetype)))
237 return true;
238 else
239 name = get_type_value (name);
240 }
241 else
242 {
243 /* In the case of:
244
245 template <class T> struct S { ~S(); };
246 int i;
247 i.~S();
248
249 NAME will be a class template. */
250 gcc_assert (DECL_CLASS_TEMPLATE_P (name));
251 return false;
252 }
253
254 if (!name || name == error_mark_node)
255 return false;
256 return same_type_p (TYPE_MAIN_VARIANT (basetype), TYPE_MAIN_VARIANT (name));
257}
258
259/* We want the address of a function or method. We avoid creating a
260 pointer-to-member function. */
261
262tree
263build_addr_func (tree function, tsubst_flags_t complain)
264{
265 tree type = TREE_TYPE (function);
266
267 /* We have to do these by hand to avoid real pointer to member
268 functions. */
269 if (TREE_CODE (type) == METHOD_TYPE)
270 {
271 if (TREE_CODE (function) == OFFSET_REF)
272 {
273 tree object = build_address (TREE_OPERAND (function, 0));
274 return get_member_function_from_ptrfunc (&object,
275 TREE_OPERAND (function, 1),
276 complain);
277 }
278 function = build_address (function);
279 }
280 else
281 function = decay_conversion (function, complain, /*reject_builtin=*/false);
282
283 return function;
284}
285
286/* Build a CALL_EXPR, we can handle FUNCTION_TYPEs, METHOD_TYPEs, or
287 POINTER_TYPE to those. Note, pointer to member function types
288 (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P) must be handled by our callers. There are
289 two variants. build_call_a is the primitive taking an array of
290 arguments, while build_call_n is a wrapper that handles varargs. */
291
292tree
293build_call_n (tree function, int n, ...)
294{
295 if (n == 0)
296 return build_call_a (function, 0, NULL);
297 else
298 {
299 tree *argarray = XALLOCAVEC (tree, n);
300 va_list ap;
301 int i;
302
303 va_start (ap, n);
304 for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
305 argarray[i] = va_arg (ap, tree);
306 va_end (ap);
307 return build_call_a (function, n, argarray);
308 }
309}
310
311/* Update various flags in cfun and the call itself based on what is being
312 called. Split out of build_call_a so that bot_manip can use it too. */
313
314void
315set_flags_from_callee (tree call)
316{
317 bool nothrow;
318 tree decl = get_callee_fndecl (call);
319
320 /* We check both the decl and the type; a function may be known not to
321 throw without being declared throw(). */
322 nothrow = decl && TREE_NOTHROW (decl);
323 if (CALL_EXPR_FN (call))
324 nothrow |= TYPE_NOTHROW_P (TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (CALL_EXPR_FN (call))));
325 else if (internal_fn_flags (CALL_EXPR_IFN (call)) & ECF_NOTHROW)
326 nothrow = true;
327
328 if (!nothrow && at_function_scope_p () && cfun && cp_function_chain)
329 cp_function_chain->can_throw = 1;
330
331 if (decl && TREE_THIS_VOLATILE (decl) && cfun && cp_function_chain)
332 current_function_returns_abnormally = 1;
333
334 TREE_NOTHROW (call) = nothrow;
335}
336
337tree
338build_call_a (tree function, int n, tree *argarray)
339{
340 tree decl;
341 tree result_type;
342 tree fntype;
343 int i;
344
345 function = build_addr_func (function, tf_warning_or_error);
346
347 gcc_assert (TYPE_PTR_P (TREE_TYPE (function)));
348 fntype = TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (function));
349 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (fntype) == FUNCTION_TYPE
350 || TREE_CODE (fntype) == METHOD_TYPE);
351 result_type = TREE_TYPE (fntype);
352 /* An rvalue has no cv-qualifiers. */
353 if (SCALAR_TYPE_P (result_type) || VOID_TYPE_P (result_type))
354 result_type = cv_unqualified (result_type);
355
356 function = build_call_array_loc (input_location,
357 result_type, function, n, argarray);
358 set_flags_from_callee (function);
359
360 decl = get_callee_fndecl (function);
361
362 if (decl && !TREE_USED (decl))
363 {
364 /* We invoke build_call directly for several library
365 functions. These may have been declared normally if
366 we're building libgcc, so we can't just check
367 DECL_ARTIFICIAL. */
368 gcc_assert (DECL_ARTIFICIAL (decl)
369 || !strncmp (IDENTIFIER_POINTER (DECL_NAME (decl)),
370 "__", 2));
371 mark_used (decl);
372 }
373
374 require_complete_eh_spec_types (fntype, decl);
375
376 TREE_HAS_CONSTRUCTOR (function) = (decl && DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (decl));
377
378 /* Don't pass empty class objects by value. This is useful
379 for tags in STL, which are used to control overload resolution.
380 We don't need to handle other cases of copying empty classes. */
381 if (! decl || ! DECL_BUILT_IN (decl))
382 for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
383 {
384 tree arg = CALL_EXPR_ARG (function, i);
385 if (is_empty_class (TREE_TYPE (arg))
386 && ! TREE_ADDRESSABLE (TREE_TYPE (arg)))
387 {
388 tree t = build0 (EMPTY_CLASS_EXPR, TREE_TYPE (arg));
389 arg = build2 (COMPOUND_EXPR, TREE_TYPE (t), arg, t);
390 CALL_EXPR_ARG (function, i) = arg;
391 }
392 }
393
394 return function;
395}

397/* New overloading code. */
398
399struct z_candidate;
400
401struct candidate_warning {
402 z_candidate *loser;
403 candidate_warning *next;
404};

406/* Information for providing diagnostics about why overloading failed. */
407
408enum rejection_reason_code {
409 rr_none,
410 rr_arity,
411 rr_explicit_conversion,
412 rr_template_conversion,
413 rr_arg_conversion,
414 rr_bad_arg_conversion,
415 rr_template_unification,
416 rr_invalid_copy,
417 rr_inherited_ctor,
418 rr_constraint_failure
419};
420
421struct conversion_info {
422 /* The index of the argument, 0-based. */
423 int n_arg;
424 /* The actual argument or its type. */
425 tree from;
426 /* The type of the parameter. */
427 tree to_type;
428};
429
430struct rejection_reason {
431 enum rejection_reason_code code;
432 union {
433 /* Information about an arity mismatch. */
434 struct {
435 /* The expected number of arguments. */
436 int expected;
437 /* The actual number of arguments in the call. */
438 int actual;
439 /* Whether the call was a varargs call. */
440 bool call_varargs_p;
441 } arity;
442 /* Information about an argument conversion mismatch. */
443 struct conversion_info conversion;
444 /* Same, but for bad argument conversions. */
445 struct conversion_info bad_conversion;
446 /* Information about template unification failures. These are the
447 parameters passed to fn_type_unification. */
448 struct {
449 tree tmpl;
450 tree explicit_targs;
451 int num_targs;
452 const tree *args;
453 unsigned int nargs;
454 tree return_type;
455 unification_kind_t strict;
456 int flags;
457 } template_unification;
458 /* Information about template instantiation failures. These are the
459 parameters passed to instantiate_template. */
460 struct {
461 tree tmpl;
462 tree targs;
463 } template_instantiation;
464 } u;
465};
466
467struct z_candidate {
468 /* The FUNCTION_DECL that will be called if this candidate is
469 selected by overload resolution. */
470 tree fn;
471 /* If not NULL_TREE, the first argument to use when calling this
472 function. */
473 tree first_arg;
474 /* The rest of the arguments to use when calling this function. If
475 there are no further arguments this may be NULL or it may be an
476 empty vector. */
477 const vec<tree, va_gc> *args;
478 /* The implicit conversion sequences for each of the arguments to
479 FN. */
480 conversion **convs;
481 /* The number of implicit conversion sequences. */
482 size_t num_convs;
483 /* If FN is a user-defined conversion, the standard conversion
484 sequence from the type returned by FN to the desired destination
485 type. */
486 conversion *second_conv;
487 struct rejection_reason *reason;
488 /* If FN is a member function, the binfo indicating the path used to
489 qualify the name of FN at the call site. This path is used to
490 determine whether or not FN is accessible if it is selected by
491 overload resolution. The DECL_CONTEXT of FN will always be a
492 (possibly improper) base of this binfo. */
493 tree access_path;
494 /* If FN is a non-static member function, the binfo indicating the
495 subobject to which the `this' pointer should be converted if FN
496 is selected by overload resolution. The type pointed to by
497 the `this' pointer must correspond to the most derived class
498 indicated by the CONVERSION_PATH. */
499 tree conversion_path;
500 tree template_decl;
501 tree explicit_targs;
502 candidate_warning *warnings;
503 z_candidate *next;
504 int viable;
505
506 /* The flags active in add_candidate. */
507 int flags;
508};
509
510/* Returns true iff T is a null pointer constant in the sense of
511 [conv.ptr]. */
512
513bool
514null_ptr_cst_p (tree t)
515{
516 tree type = TREE_TYPE (t);
517
518 /* [conv.ptr]
519
520 A null pointer constant is an integral constant expression
521 (_expr.const_) rvalue of integer type that evaluates to zero or
522 an rvalue of type std::nullptr_t. */
523 if (NULLPTR_TYPE_P (type))
524 return true;
525
526 if (cxx_dialect >= cxx11)
527 {
528 /* Core issue 903 says only literal 0 is a null pointer constant. */
529 if (TREE_CODE (type) == INTEGER_TYPE
530 && !char_type_p (type)
531 && TREE_CODE (t) == INTEGER_CST
532 && integer_zerop (t)
533 && !TREE_OVERFLOW (t))
534 return true;
535 }
536 else if (CP_INTEGRAL_TYPE_P (type))
537 {
538 t = fold_non_dependent_expr (t);
539 STRIP_NOPS (t);
540 if (integer_zerop (t) && !TREE_OVERFLOW (t))
541 return true;
542 }
543
544 return false;
545}
546
547/* Returns true iff T is a null member pointer value (4.11). */
548
549bool
550null_member_pointer_value_p (tree t)
551{
552 tree type = TREE_TYPE (t);
553 if (!type)
554 return false;
555 else if (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (type))
556 return (TREE_CODE (t) == CONSTRUCTOR
557 && integer_zerop (CONSTRUCTOR_ELT (t, 0)->value));
558 else if (TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (type))
559 return integer_all_onesp (t);
560 else
561 return false;
562}
563
564/* Returns nonzero if PARMLIST consists of only default parms,
565 ellipsis, and/or undeduced parameter packs. */
566
567bool
568sufficient_parms_p (const_tree parmlist)
569{
570 for (; parmlist && parmlist != void_list_node;
571 parmlist = TREE_CHAIN (parmlist))
572 if (!TREE_PURPOSE (parmlist)
573 && !PACK_EXPANSION_P (TREE_VALUE (parmlist)))
574 return false;
575 return true;
576}
577
578/* Allocate N bytes of memory from the conversion obstack. The memory
579 is zeroed before being returned. */
580
581static void *
582conversion_obstack_alloc (size_t n)
583{
584 void *p;
585 if (!conversion_obstack_initialized)
586 {
587 gcc_obstack_init (&conversion_obstack);
588 conversion_obstack_initialized = true;
589 }
590 p = obstack_alloc (&conversion_obstack, n);
591 memset (p, 0, n);
592 return p;
593}
594
595/* Allocate rejection reasons. */
596
597static struct rejection_reason *
598alloc_rejection (enum rejection_reason_code code)
599{
600 struct rejection_reason *p;
601 p = (struct rejection_reason *) conversion_obstack_alloc (sizeof *p);
602 p->code = code;
603 return p;
604}
605
606static struct rejection_reason *
607arity_rejection (tree first_arg, int expected, int actual)
608{
609 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_arity);
610 int adjust = first_arg != NULL_TREE;
611 r->u.arity.expected = expected - adjust;
612 r->u.arity.actual = actual - adjust;
613 return r;
614}
615
616static struct rejection_reason *
617arg_conversion_rejection (tree first_arg, int n_arg, tree from, tree to)
618{
619 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_arg_conversion);
620 int adjust = first_arg != NULL_TREE;
621 r->u.conversion.n_arg = n_arg - adjust;
622 r->u.conversion.from = from;
623 r->u.conversion.to_type = to;
624 return r;
625}
626
627static struct rejection_reason *
628bad_arg_conversion_rejection (tree first_arg, int n_arg, tree from, tree to)
629{
630 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_bad_arg_conversion);
631 int adjust = first_arg != NULL_TREE;
632 r->u.bad_conversion.n_arg = n_arg - adjust;
633 r->u.bad_conversion.from = from;
634 r->u.bad_conversion.to_type = to;
635 return r;
636}
637
638static struct rejection_reason *
639explicit_conversion_rejection (tree from, tree to)
640{
641 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_explicit_conversion);
642 r->u.conversion.n_arg = 0;
643 r->u.conversion.from = from;
644 r->u.conversion.to_type = to;
645 return r;
646}
647
648static struct rejection_reason *
649template_conversion_rejection (tree from, tree to)
650{
651 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_template_conversion);
652 r->u.conversion.n_arg = 0;
653 r->u.conversion.from = from;
654 r->u.conversion.to_type = to;
655 return r;
656}
657
658static struct rejection_reason *
659template_unification_rejection (tree tmpl, tree explicit_targs, tree targs,
660 const tree *args, unsigned int nargs,
661 tree return_type, unification_kind_t strict,
662 int flags)
663{
664 size_t args_n_bytes = sizeof (*args) * nargs;
665 tree *args1 = (tree *) conversion_obstack_alloc (args_n_bytes);
666 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_template_unification);
667 r->u.template_unification.tmpl = tmpl;
668 r->u.template_unification.explicit_targs = explicit_targs;
669 r->u.template_unification.num_targs = TREE_VEC_LENGTH (targs);
670 /* Copy args to our own storage. */
671 memcpy (args1, args, args_n_bytes);
672 r->u.template_unification.args = args1;
673 r->u.template_unification.nargs = nargs;
674 r->u.template_unification.return_type = return_type;
675 r->u.template_unification.strict = strict;
676 r->u.template_unification.flags = flags;
677 return r;
678}
679
680static struct rejection_reason *
681template_unification_error_rejection (void)
682{
683 return alloc_rejection (rr_template_unification);
684}

690 return r;
691}

693static struct rejection_reason *
694inherited_ctor_rejection (void)

698}

700// Build a constraint failure record, saving information into the
701// template_instantiation field of the rejection. If FN is not a template
702// declaration, the TMPL member is the FN declaration and TARGS is empty.
703
704static struct rejection_reason *
705constraint_failure (tree fn)
706{
707 struct rejection_reason *r = alloc_rejection (rr_constraint_failure);
708 if (tree ti = DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO (fn))
709 {
710 r->u.template_instantiation.tmpl = TI_TEMPLATE (ti);
711 r->u.template_instantiation.targs = TI_ARGS (ti);
712 }
713 else
714 {
715 r->u.template_instantiation.tmpl = fn;
716 r->u.template_instantiation.targs = NULL_TREE;
717 }
718 return r;
719}
720
721/* Dynamically allocate a conversion. */
722
723static conversion *
724alloc_conversion (conversion_kind kind)
725{
726 conversion *c;
727 c = (conversion *) conversion_obstack_alloc (sizeof (conversion));
728 c->kind = kind;
729 return c;
730}
731
732/* Make sure that all memory on the conversion obstack has been
733 freed. */
734
735void
736validate_conversion_obstack (void)
737{
738 if (conversion_obstack_initialized)
739 gcc_assert ((obstack_next_free (&conversion_obstack)
740 == obstack_base (&conversion_obstack)));
741}
742
743/* Dynamically allocate an array of N conversions. */
744
745static conversion **
746alloc_conversions (size_t n)
747{
748 return (conversion **) conversion_obstack_alloc (n * sizeof (conversion *));
749}
750
751static conversion *
752build_conv (conversion_kind code, tree type, conversion *from)
753{
754 conversion *t;
755 conversion_rank rank = CONVERSION_RANK (from);
756
757 /* Note that the caller is responsible for filling in t->cand for
758 user-defined conversions. */
759 t = alloc_conversion (code);
760 t->type = type;
761 t->u.next = from;
762
763 switch (code)
764 {
765 case ck_ptr:
766 case ck_pmem:
767 case ck_base:
768 case ck_std:
769 if (rank < cr_std)
770 rank = cr_std;
771 break;
772
773 case ck_qual:
774 case ck_fnptr:
775 if (rank < cr_exact)
776 rank = cr_exact;
777 break;
778
779 default:
780 break;
781 }
782 t->rank = rank;
783 t->user_conv_p = (code == ck_user || from->user_conv_p);
784 t->bad_p = from->bad_p;
785 t->base_p = false;
786 return t;
787}
788
789/* Represent a conversion from CTOR, a braced-init-list, to TYPE, a
790 specialization of std::initializer_list<T>, if such a conversion is
791 possible. */
792
793static conversion *
794build_list_conv (tree type, tree ctor, int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
795{
796 tree elttype = TREE_VEC_ELT (CLASSTYPE_TI_ARGS (type), 0);
797 unsigned len = CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (ctor);
798 conversion **subconvs = alloc_conversions (len);
799 conversion *t;
800 unsigned i;
801 tree val;
802
803 /* Within a list-initialization we can have more user-defined
804 conversions. */
805 flags &= ~LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION;
806 /* But no narrowing conversions. */
807 flags |= LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING;
808
809 /* Can't make an array of these types. */
810 if (TREE_CODE (elttype) == REFERENCE_TYPE
811 || TREE_CODE (elttype) == FUNCTION_TYPE
812 || VOID_TYPE_P (elttype))
813 return NULL;
814
815 FOR_EACH_CONSTRUCTOR_VALUE (CONSTRUCTOR_ELTS (ctor), i, val)
816 {
817 conversion *sub
818 = implicit_conversion (elttype, TREE_TYPE (val), val,
819 false, flags, complain);
820 if (sub == NULL)
821 return NULL;
822
823 subconvs[i] = sub;
824 }
825
826 t = alloc_conversion (ck_list);
827 t->type = type;
828 t->u.list = subconvs;
829 t->rank = cr_exact;
830
831 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
832 {
833 conversion *sub = subconvs[i];
834 if (sub->rank > t->rank)
835 t->rank = sub->rank;
836 if (sub->user_conv_p)
837 t->user_conv_p = true;
838 if (sub->bad_p)
839 t->bad_p = true;
840 }
841
842 return t;
843}
844
845/* Return the next conversion of the conversion chain (if applicable),
846 or NULL otherwise. Please use this function instead of directly
847 accessing fields of struct conversion. */
848
849static conversion *
850next_conversion (conversion *conv)
851{
852 if (conv == NULL
853 || conv->kind == ck_identity
854 || conv->kind == ck_ambig
855 || conv->kind == ck_list)
856 return NULL;
857 return conv->u.next;
858}
859
860/* Subroutine of build_aggr_conv: check whether CTOR, a braced-init-list,
861 is a valid aggregate initializer for array type ATYPE. */
862
863static bool
864can_convert_array (tree atype, tree ctor, int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
865{
866 unsigned i;
867 tree elttype = TREE_TYPE (atype);
868 for (i = 0; i < CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (ctor); ++i)
869 {
870 tree val = CONSTRUCTOR_ELT (ctor, i)->value;
871 bool ok;
872 if (TREE_CODE (elttype) == ARRAY_TYPE
873 && TREE_CODE (val) == CONSTRUCTOR)
874 ok = can_convert_array (elttype, val, flags, complain);
875 else
876 ok = can_convert_arg (elttype, TREE_TYPE (val), val, flags,
877 complain);
878 if (!ok)
879 return false;
880 }
881 return true;
882}
883
884/* Represent a conversion from CTOR, a braced-init-list, to TYPE, an
885 aggregate class, if such a conversion is possible. */
886
887static conversion *
888build_aggr_conv (tree type, tree ctor, int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
889{
890 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT i = 0;
891 conversion *c;
892 tree field = next_initializable_field (TYPE_FIELDS (type));
893 tree empty_ctor = NULL_TREE;
894
895 /* We already called reshape_init in implicit_conversion. */
896
897 /* The conversions within the init-list aren't affected by the enclosing
898 context; they're always simple copy-initialization. */
899 flags = LOOKUP_IMPLICIT|LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING;
900
901 for (; field; field = next_initializable_field (DECL_CHAIN (field)))
902 {
903 tree ftype = TREE_TYPE (field);
904 tree val;
905 bool ok;
906
907 if (i < CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (ctor))
908 val = CONSTRUCTOR_ELT (ctor, i)->value;
909 else if (DECL_INITIAL (field))
910 val = get_nsdmi (field, /*ctor*/false);
911 else if (TREE_CODE (ftype) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
912 /* Value-initialization of reference is ill-formed. */
913 return NULL;
914 else
915 {
916 if (empty_ctor == NULL_TREE)
917 empty_ctor = build_constructor (init_list_type_node, NULL);
918 val = empty_ctor;
919 }
920 ++i;
921
922 if (TREE_CODE (ftype) == ARRAY_TYPE
923 && TREE_CODE (val) == CONSTRUCTOR)
924 ok = can_convert_array (ftype, val, flags, complain);
925 else
926 ok = can_convert_arg (ftype, TREE_TYPE (val), val, flags,
927 complain);
928
929 if (!ok)
930 return NULL;
931
932 if (TREE_CODE (type) == UNION_TYPE)
933 break;
934 }
935
936 if (i < CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (ctor))
937 return NULL;
938
939 c = alloc_conversion (ck_aggr);
940 c->type = type;
941 c->rank = cr_exact;
942 c->user_conv_p = true;
943 c->check_narrowing = true;
944 c->u.next = NULL;
945 return c;
946}
947
948/* Represent a conversion from CTOR, a braced-init-list, to TYPE, an
949 array type, if such a conversion is possible. */
950
951static conversion *
952build_array_conv (tree type, tree ctor, int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
953{
954 conversion *c;
955 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT len = CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (ctor);
956 tree elttype = TREE_TYPE (type);
957 unsigned i;
958 tree val;
959 bool bad = false;
960 bool user = false;
961 enum conversion_rank rank = cr_exact;
962
963 /* We might need to propagate the size from the element to the array. */
964 complete_type (type);
965
966 if (TYPE_DOMAIN (type)
967 && !variably_modified_type_p (TYPE_DOMAIN (type), NULL_TREE))
968 {
969 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT alen = tree_to_uhwi (array_type_nelts_top (type));
970 if (alen < len)
971 return NULL;
972 }
973
974 flags = LOOKUP_IMPLICIT|LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING;
975
976 FOR_EACH_CONSTRUCTOR_VALUE (CONSTRUCTOR_ELTS (ctor), i, val)
977 {
978 conversion *sub
979 = implicit_conversion (elttype, TREE_TYPE (val), val,
980 false, flags, complain);
981 if (sub == NULL)
982 return NULL;
983
984 if (sub->rank > rank)
985 rank = sub->rank;
986 if (sub->user_conv_p)
987 user = true;
988 if (sub->bad_p)
989 bad = true;
990 }
991
992 c = alloc_conversion (ck_aggr);
993 c->type = type;
994 c->rank = rank;
995 c->user_conv_p = user;
996 c->bad_p = bad;
997 c->u.next = NULL;
998 return c;
999}
1000
1001/* Represent a conversion from CTOR, a braced-init-list, to TYPE, a
1002 complex type, if such a conversion is possible. */
1003
1004static conversion *
1005build_complex_conv (tree type, tree ctor, int flags,
1006 tsubst_flags_t complain)
1007{
1008 conversion *c;
1009 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT len = CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (ctor);
1010 tree elttype = TREE_TYPE (type);
1011 unsigned i;
1012 tree val;
1013 bool bad = false;
1014 bool user = false;
1015 enum conversion_rank rank = cr_exact;
1016
1017 if (len != 2)
1018 return NULL;
1019
1020 flags = LOOKUP_IMPLICIT|LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING;
1021
1022 FOR_EACH_CONSTRUCTOR_VALUE (CONSTRUCTOR_ELTS (ctor), i, val)
1023 {
1024 conversion *sub
1025 = implicit_conversion (elttype, TREE_TYPE (val), val,
1026 false, flags, complain);
1027 if (sub == NULL)
1028 return NULL;
1029
1030 if (sub->rank > rank)
1031 rank = sub->rank;
1032 if (sub->user_conv_p)
1033 user = true;
1034 if (sub->bad_p)
1035 bad = true;
1036 }
1037
1038 c = alloc_conversion (ck_aggr);
1039 c->type = type;
1040 c->rank = rank;
1041 c->user_conv_p = user;
1042 c->bad_p = bad;
1043 c->u.next = NULL;
1044 return c;
1045}
1046
1047/* Build a representation of the identity conversion from EXPR to
1048 itself. The TYPE should match the type of EXPR, if EXPR is non-NULL. */
1049
1050static conversion *
1051build_identity_conv (tree type, tree expr)
1052{
1053 conversion *c;
1054
1055 c = alloc_conversion (ck_identity);
1056 c->type = type;
1057 c->u.expr = expr;
1058
1059 return c;
1060}
1061
1062/* Converting from EXPR to TYPE was ambiguous in the sense that there
1063 were multiple user-defined conversions to accomplish the job.
1064 Build a conversion that indicates that ambiguity. */
1065
1066static conversion *
1067build_ambiguous_conv (tree type, tree expr)
1068{
1069 conversion *c;
1070
1071 c = alloc_conversion (ck_ambig);
1072 c->type = type;
1073 c->u.expr = expr;
1074
1075 return c;
1076}
1077
1078tree
1079strip_top_quals (tree t)
1080{
1081 if (TREE_CODE (t) == ARRAY_TYPE)
1082 return t;
1083 return cp_build_qualified_type (t, 0);
1084}
1085
1086/* Returns the standard conversion path (see [conv]) from type FROM to type
1087 TO, if any. For proper handling of null pointer constants, you must
1088 also pass the expression EXPR to convert from. If C_CAST_P is true,
1089 this conversion is coming from a C-style cast. */
1090
1091static conversion *
1092standard_conversion (tree to, tree from, tree expr, bool c_cast_p,
1093 int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
1094{
1095 enum tree_code fcode, tcode;
1096 conversion *conv;
1097 bool fromref = false;
1098 tree qualified_to;
1099
1100 to = non_reference (to);
1101 if (TREE_CODE (from) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
1102 {
1103 fromref = true;
1104 from = TREE_TYPE (from);
1105 }
1106 qualified_to = to;
1107 to = strip_top_quals (to);
1108 from = strip_top_quals (from);
1109
1110 if (expr && type_unknown_p (expr))
1111 {
1112 if (TYPE_PTRFN_P (to) || TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (to))
1113 {
1114 tsubst_flags_t tflags = tf_conv;
1115 expr = instantiate_type (to, expr, tflags);
1116 if (expr == error_mark_node)
1117 return NULL;
1118 from = TREE_TYPE (expr);
1119 }
1120 else if (TREE_CODE (to) == BOOLEAN_TYPE)
1121 {
1122 /* Necessary for eg, TEMPLATE_ID_EXPRs (c++/50961). */
1123 expr = resolve_nondeduced_context (expr, complain);
1124 from = TREE_TYPE (expr);
1125 }
1126 }
1127
1128 fcode = TREE_CODE (from);
1129 tcode = TREE_CODE (to);
1130
1131 conv = build_identity_conv (from, expr);
1132 if (fcode == FUNCTION_TYPE || fcode == ARRAY_TYPE)
1133 {
1134 from = type_decays_to (from);
1135 fcode = TREE_CODE (from);
1136 conv = build_conv (ck_lvalue, from, conv);
1137 }
1138 /* Wrapping a ck_rvalue around a class prvalue (as a result of using
1139 obvalue_p) seems odd, since it's already a prvalue, but that's how we
1140 express the copy constructor call required by copy-initialization. */
1141 else if (fromref || (expr && obvalue_p (expr)))
1142 {
1143 if (expr)
1144 {
1145 tree bitfield_type;
1146 bitfield_type = is_bitfield_expr_with_lowered_type (expr);
1147 if (bitfield_type)
1148 {
1149 from = strip_top_quals (bitfield_type);
1150 fcode = TREE_CODE (from);
1151 }
1152 }
1153 conv = build_conv (ck_rvalue, from, conv);
1154 if (flags & LOOKUP_PREFER_RVALUE)
1155 conv->rvaluedness_matches_p = true;
1156 }
1157
1158 /* Allow conversion between `__complex__' data types. */
1159 if (tcode == COMPLEX_TYPE && fcode == COMPLEX_TYPE)
1160 {
1161 /* The standard conversion sequence to convert FROM to TO is
1162 the standard conversion sequence to perform componentwise
1163 conversion. */
1164 conversion *part_conv = standard_conversion
1165 (TREE_TYPE (to), TREE_TYPE (from), NULL_TREE, c_cast_p, flags,
1166 complain);
1167
1168 if (part_conv)
1169 {
1170 conv = build_conv (part_conv->kind, to, conv);
1171 conv->rank = part_conv->rank;
1172 }
1173 else
1174 conv = NULL;
1175
1176 return conv;
1177 }
1178
1179 if (same_type_p (from, to))
1180 {
1181 if (CLASS_TYPE_P (to) && conv->kind == ck_rvalue)
1182 conv->type = qualified_to;
1183 return conv;
1184 }
1185
1186 /* [conv.ptr]
1187 A null pointer constant can be converted to a pointer type; ... A
1188 null pointer constant of integral type can be converted to an
1189 rvalue of type std::nullptr_t. */
1190 if ((tcode == POINTER_TYPE || TYPE_PTRMEM_P (to)
1191 || NULLPTR_TYPE_P (to))
1192 && ((expr && null_ptr_cst_p (expr))
1193 || NULLPTR_TYPE_P (from)))
1194 conv = build_conv (ck_std, to, conv);
1195 else if ((tcode == INTEGER_TYPE && fcode == POINTER_TYPE)
1196 || (tcode == POINTER_TYPE && fcode == INTEGER_TYPE))
1197 {
1198 /* For backwards brain damage compatibility, allow interconversion of
1199 pointers and integers with a pedwarn. */
1200 conv = build_conv (ck_std, to, conv);
1201 conv->bad_p = true;
1202 }
1203 else if (UNSCOPED_ENUM_P (to) && fcode == INTEGER_TYPE)
1204 {
1205 /* For backwards brain damage compatibility, allow interconversion of
1206 enums and integers with a pedwarn. */
1207 conv = build_conv (ck_std, to, conv);
1208 conv->bad_p = true;
1209 }
1210 else if ((tcode == POINTER_TYPE && fcode == POINTER_TYPE)
1211 || (TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (to) && TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (from)))
1212 {
1213 tree to_pointee;
1214 tree from_pointee;
1215
1216 if (tcode == POINTER_TYPE)
1217 {
1218 to_pointee = TREE_TYPE (to);
1219 from_pointee = TREE_TYPE (from);
1220
1221 /* Since this is the target of a pointer, it can't have function
1222 qualifiers, so any TYPE_QUALS must be for attributes const or
1223 noreturn. Strip them. */
1224 if (TREE_CODE (to_pointee) == FUNCTION_TYPE
1225 && TYPE_QUALS (to_pointee))
1226 to_pointee = build_qualified_type (to_pointee, TYPE_UNQUALIFIED);
1227 if (TREE_CODE (from_pointee) == FUNCTION_TYPE
1228 && TYPE_QUALS (from_pointee))
1229 from_pointee = build_qualified_type (from_pointee, TYPE_UNQUALIFIED);
1230 }
1231 else
1232 {
1233 to_pointee = TYPE_PTRMEM_POINTED_TO_TYPE (to);
1234 from_pointee = TYPE_PTRMEM_POINTED_TO_TYPE (from);
1235 }
1236
1237 if (tcode == POINTER_TYPE
1238 && same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p (from_pointee,
1239 to_pointee))
1240 ;
1241 else if (VOID_TYPE_P (to_pointee)
1242 && !TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (from)
1243 && TREE_CODE (from_pointee) != FUNCTION_TYPE)
1244 {
1245 tree nfrom = TREE_TYPE (from);
1246 /* Don't try to apply restrict to void. */
1247 int quals = cp_type_quals (nfrom) & ~TYPE_QUAL_RESTRICT;
1248 from_pointee = cp_build_qualified_type (void_type_node, quals);
1249 from = build_pointer_type (from_pointee);
1250 conv = build_conv (ck_ptr, from, conv);
1251 }
1252 else if (TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (from))
1253 {
1254 tree fbase = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (from);
1255 tree tbase = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (to);
1256
1257 if (DERIVED_FROM_P (fbase, tbase)
1258 && (same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p
1259 (from_pointee, to_pointee)))
1260 {
1261 from = build_ptrmem_type (tbase, from_pointee);
1262 conv = build_conv (ck_pmem, from, conv);
1263 }
1264 else if (!same_type_p (fbase, tbase))
1265 return NULL;
1266 }
1267 else if (CLASS_TYPE_P (from_pointee)
1268 && CLASS_TYPE_P (to_pointee)
1269 /* [conv.ptr]
1270
1271 An rvalue of type "pointer to cv D," where D is a
1272 class type, can be converted to an rvalue of type
1273 "pointer to cv B," where B is a base class (clause
1274 _class.derived_) of D. If B is an inaccessible
1275 (clause _class.access_) or ambiguous
1276 (_class.member.lookup_) base class of D, a program
1277 that necessitates this conversion is ill-formed.
1278 Therefore, we use DERIVED_FROM_P, and do not check
1279 access or uniqueness. */
1280 && DERIVED_FROM_P (to_pointee, from_pointee))
1281 {
1282 from_pointee
1283 = cp_build_qualified_type (to_pointee,
1284 cp_type_quals (from_pointee));
1285 from = build_pointer_type (from_pointee);
1286 conv = build_conv (ck_ptr, from, conv);
1287 conv->base_p = true;
1288 }
1289
1290 if (same_type_p (from, to))
1291 /* OK */;
1292 else if (c_cast_p && comp_ptr_ttypes_const (to, from))
1293 /* In a C-style cast, we ignore CV-qualification because we
1294 are allowed to perform a static_cast followed by a
1295 const_cast. */
1296 conv = build_conv (ck_qual, to, conv);
1297 else if (!c_cast_p && comp_ptr_ttypes (to_pointee, from_pointee))
1298 conv = build_conv (ck_qual, to, conv);
1299 else if (expr && string_conv_p (to, expr, 0))
1300 /* converting from string constant to char *. */
1301 conv = build_conv (ck_qual, to, conv);
1302 else if (fnptr_conv_p (to, from))
1303 conv = build_conv (ck_fnptr, to, conv);
1304 /* Allow conversions among compatible ObjC pointer types (base
1305 conversions have been already handled above). */
1306 else if (c_dialect_objc ()
1307 && objc_compare_types (to, from, -4, NULL_TREE))
1308 conv = build_conv (ck_ptr, to, conv);
1309 else if (ptr_reasonably_similar (to_pointee, from_pointee))
1310 {
1311 conv = build_conv (ck_ptr, to, conv);
1312 conv->bad_p = true;
1313 }
1314 else
1315 return NULL;
1316
1317 from = to;
1318 }
1319 else if (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (to) && TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (from))
1320 {
1321 tree fromfn = TREE_TYPE (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_FN_TYPE (from));
1322 tree tofn = TREE_TYPE (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_FN_TYPE (to));
1323 tree fbase = class_of_this_parm (fromfn);
1324 tree tbase = class_of_this_parm (tofn);
1325
1326 if (!DERIVED_FROM_P (fbase, tbase))
1327 return NULL;
1328
1329 tree fstat = static_fn_type (fromfn);
1330 tree tstat = static_fn_type (tofn);
1331 if (same_type_p (tstat, fstat)
1332 || fnptr_conv_p (tstat, fstat))
1333 /* OK */;
1334 else
1335 return NULL;
1336
1337 if (!same_type_p (fbase, tbase))
1338 {
1339 from = build_memfn_type (fstat,
1340 tbase,
1341 cp_type_quals (tbase),
1342 type_memfn_rqual (tofn));
1343 from = build_ptrmemfunc_type (build_pointer_type (from));
1344 conv = build_conv (ck_pmem, from, conv);
1345 conv->base_p = true;
1346 }
1347 if (fnptr_conv_p (tstat, fstat))
1348 conv = build_conv (ck_fnptr, to, conv);
1349 }
1350 else if (tcode == BOOLEAN_TYPE)
1351 {
1352 /* [conv.bool]
1353
1354 A prvalue of arithmetic, unscoped enumeration, pointer, or pointer
1355 to member type can be converted to a prvalue of type bool. ...
1356 For direct-initialization (8.5 [dcl.init]), a prvalue of type
1357 std::nullptr_t can be converted to a prvalue of type bool; */
1358 if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (from)
1359 || UNSCOPED_ENUM_P (from)
1360 || fcode == POINTER_TYPE
1361 || TYPE_PTRMEM_P (from)
1362 || NULLPTR_TYPE_P (from))
1363 {
1364 conv = build_conv (ck_std, to, conv);
1365 if (fcode == POINTER_TYPE
1366 || TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (from)
1367 || (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (from)
1368 && conv->rank < cr_pbool)
1369 || NULLPTR_TYPE_P (from))
1370 conv->rank = cr_pbool;
1371 if (NULLPTR_TYPE_P (from) && (flags & LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING))
1372 conv->bad_p = true;
1373 return conv;
1374 }
1375
1376 return NULL;
1377 }
1378 /* We don't check for ENUMERAL_TYPE here because there are no standard
1379 conversions to enum type. */
1380 /* As an extension, allow conversion to complex type. */
1381 else if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (to))
1382 {
1383 if (! (INTEGRAL_CODE_P (fcode)
1384 || (fcode == REAL_TYPE && !(flags & LOOKUP_NO_NON_INTEGRAL)))
1385 || SCOPED_ENUM_P (from))
1386 return NULL;
1387 conv = build_conv (ck_std, to, conv);
1388
1389 /* Give this a better rank if it's a promotion. */
1390 if (same_type_p (to, type_promotes_to (from))
1391 && next_conversion (conv)->rank <= cr_promotion)
1392 conv->rank = cr_promotion;
1393 }
1394 else if (fcode == VECTOR_TYPE && tcode == VECTOR_TYPE
1395 && vector_types_convertible_p (from, to, false))
1396 return build_conv (ck_std, to, conv);
1397 else if (MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (to) && MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (from)
1398 && is_properly_derived_from (from, to))
1399 {
1400 if (conv->kind == ck_rvalue)
1401 conv = next_conversion (conv);
1402 conv = build_conv (ck_base, to, conv);
1403 /* The derived-to-base conversion indicates the initialization
1404 of a parameter with base type from an object of a derived
1405 type. A temporary object is created to hold the result of
1406 the conversion unless we're binding directly to a reference. */
1407 conv->need_temporary_p = !(flags & LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND);
1408 }
1409 else
1410 return NULL;
1411
1412 if (flags & LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING)
1413 conv->check_narrowing = true;
1414
1415 return conv;
1416}
1417
1418/* Returns nonzero if T1 is reference-related to T2. */
1419
1420bool
1421reference_related_p (tree t1, tree t2)
1422{
1423 if (t1 == error_mark_node || t2 == error_mark_node)
1424 return false;
1425
1426 t1 = TYPE_MAIN_VARIANT (t1);
1427 t2 = TYPE_MAIN_VARIANT (t2);
1428
1429 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1430
1431 Given types "cv1 T1" and "cv2 T2," "cv1 T1" is reference-related
1432 to "cv2 T2" if T1 is the same type as T2, or T1 is a base class
1433 of T2. */
1434 return (same_type_p (t1, t2)
1435 || (CLASS_TYPE_P (t1) && CLASS_TYPE_P (t2)
1436 && DERIVED_FROM_P (t1, t2)));
1437}
1438
1439/* Returns nonzero if T1 is reference-compatible with T2. */
1440
1441static bool
1442reference_compatible_p (tree t1, tree t2)
1443{
1444 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1445
1446 "cv1 T1" is reference compatible with "cv2 T2" if
1447 * T1 is reference-related to T2 or
1448 * T2 is "noexcept function" and T1 is "function", where the
1449 function types are otherwise the same,
1450 and cv1 is the same cv-qualification as, or greater cv-qualification
1451 than, cv2. */
1452 return ((reference_related_p (t1, t2)
1453 || fnptr_conv_p (t1, t2))
1454 && at_least_as_qualified_p (t1, t2));
1455}
1456
1457/* A reference of the indicated TYPE is being bound directly to the
1458 expression represented by the implicit conversion sequence CONV.
1459 Return a conversion sequence for this binding. */
1460
1461static conversion *
1462direct_reference_binding (tree type, conversion *conv)
1463{
1464 tree t;
1465
1466 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (type) == REFERENCE_TYPE);
1467 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (conv->type) != REFERENCE_TYPE);
1468
1469 t = TREE_TYPE (type);
1470
1471 /* [over.ics.rank]
1472
1473 When a parameter of reference type binds directly
1474 (_dcl.init.ref_) to an argument expression, the implicit
1475 conversion sequence is the identity conversion, unless the
1476 argument expression has a type that is a derived class of the
1477 parameter type, in which case the implicit conversion sequence is
1478 a derived-to-base Conversion.
1479
1480 If the parameter binds directly to the result of applying a
1481 conversion function to the argument expression, the implicit
1482 conversion sequence is a user-defined conversion sequence
1483 (_over.ics.user_), with the second standard conversion sequence
1484 either an identity conversion or, if the conversion function
1485 returns an entity of a type that is a derived class of the
1486 parameter type, a derived-to-base conversion. */
1487 if (is_properly_derived_from (conv->type, t))
1488 {
1489 /* Represent the derived-to-base conversion. */
1490 conv = build_conv (ck_base, t, conv);
1491 /* We will actually be binding to the base-class subobject in
1492 the derived class, so we mark this conversion appropriately.
1493 That way, convert_like knows not to generate a temporary. */
1494 conv->need_temporary_p = false;
1495 }
1496 return build_conv (ck_ref_bind, type, conv);
1497}
1498
1499/* Returns the conversion path from type FROM to reference type TO for
1500 purposes of reference binding. For lvalue binding, either pass a
1501 reference type to FROM or an lvalue expression to EXPR. If the
1502 reference will be bound to a temporary, NEED_TEMPORARY_P is set for
1503 the conversion returned. If C_CAST_P is true, this
1504 conversion is coming from a C-style cast. */
1505
1506static conversion *
1507reference_binding (tree rto, tree rfrom, tree expr, bool c_cast_p, int flags,
1508 tsubst_flags_t complain)
1509{
1510 conversion *conv = NULL;
1511 tree to = TREE_TYPE (rto);
1512 tree from = rfrom;
1513 tree tfrom;
1514 bool related_p;
1515 bool compatible_p;
1516 cp_lvalue_kind gl_kind;
1517 bool is_lvalue;
1518
1519 if (TREE_CODE (to) == FUNCTION_TYPE && expr && type_unknown_p (expr))
1520 {
1521 expr = instantiate_type (to, expr, tf_none);
1522 if (expr == error_mark_node)
1523 return NULL;
1524 from = TREE_TYPE (expr);
1525 }
1526
1527 if (expr && BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (expr))
1528 {
1529 maybe_warn_cpp0x (CPP0X_INITIALIZER_LISTS);
1530 /* DR 1288: Otherwise, if the initializer list has a single element
1531 of type E and ... [T's] referenced type is reference-related to E,
1532 the object or reference is initialized from that element... */
1533 if (CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (expr) == 1)
1534 {
1535 tree elt = CONSTRUCTOR_ELT (expr, 0)->value;
1536 if (error_operand_p (elt))
1537 return NULL;
1538 tree etype = TREE_TYPE (elt);
1539 if (reference_related_p (to, etype))
1540 {
1541 expr = elt;
1542 from = etype;
1543 goto skip;
1544 }
1545 }
1546 /* Otherwise, if T is a reference type, a prvalue temporary of the
1547 type referenced by T is copy-list-initialized or
1548 direct-list-initialized, depending on the kind of initialization
1549 for the reference, and the reference is bound to that temporary. */
1550 conv = implicit_conversion (to, from, expr, c_cast_p,
1551 flags|LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND, complain);
1552 skip:;
1553 }
1554
1555 if (TREE_CODE (from) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
1556 {
1557 from = TREE_TYPE (from);
1558 if (!TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rfrom)
1559 || TREE_CODE (from) == FUNCTION_TYPE)
1560 gl_kind = clk_ordinary;
1561 else
1562 gl_kind = clk_rvalueref;
1563 }
1564 else if (expr)
1565 gl_kind = lvalue_kind (expr);
1566 else if (CLASS_TYPE_P (from)
1567 || TREE_CODE (from) == ARRAY_TYPE)
1568 gl_kind = clk_class;
1569 else
1570 gl_kind = clk_none;
1571
1572 /* Don't allow a class prvalue when LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND. */
1573 if ((flags & LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND)
1574 && (gl_kind & clk_class))
1575 gl_kind = clk_none;
1576
1577 /* Same mask as real_lvalue_p. */
1578 is_lvalue = gl_kind && !(gl_kind & (clk_rvalueref|clk_class));
1579
1580 tfrom = from;
1581 if ((gl_kind & clk_bitfield) != 0)
1582 tfrom = unlowered_expr_type (expr);
1583
1584 /* Figure out whether or not the types are reference-related and
1585 reference compatible. We have to do this after stripping
1586 references from FROM. */
1587 related_p = reference_related_p (to, tfrom);
1588 /* If this is a C cast, first convert to an appropriately qualified
1589 type, so that we can later do a const_cast to the desired type. */
1590 if (related_p && c_cast_p
1591 && !at_least_as_qualified_p (to, tfrom))
1592 to = cp_build_qualified_type (to, cp_type_quals (tfrom));
1593 compatible_p = reference_compatible_p (to, tfrom);
1594
1595 /* Directly bind reference when target expression's type is compatible with
1596 the reference and expression is an lvalue. In DR391, the wording in
1597 [8.5.3/5 dcl.init.ref] is changed to also require direct bindings for
1598 const and rvalue references to rvalues of compatible class type.
1599 We should also do direct bindings for non-class xvalues. */
1600 if ((related_p || compatible_p) && gl_kind)
1601 {
1602 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1603
1604 If the initializer expression
1605
1606 -- is an lvalue (but not an lvalue for a bit-field), and "cv1 T1"
1607 is reference-compatible with "cv2 T2,"
1608
1609 the reference is bound directly to the initializer expression
1610 lvalue.
1611
1612 [...]
1613 If the initializer expression is an rvalue, with T2 a class type,
1614 and "cv1 T1" is reference-compatible with "cv2 T2", the reference
1615 is bound to the object represented by the rvalue or to a sub-object
1616 within that object. */
1617
1618 conv = build_identity_conv (tfrom, expr);
1619 conv = direct_reference_binding (rto, conv);
1620
1621 if (flags & LOOKUP_PREFER_RVALUE)
1622 /* The top-level caller requested that we pretend that the lvalue
1623 be treated as an rvalue. */
1624 conv->rvaluedness_matches_p = TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto);
1625 else if (TREE_CODE (rfrom) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
1626 /* Handle rvalue reference to function properly. */
1627 conv->rvaluedness_matches_p
1628 = (TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto) == TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rfrom));
1629 else
1630 conv->rvaluedness_matches_p
1631 = (TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto) == !is_lvalue);
1632
1633 if ((gl_kind & clk_bitfield) != 0
1634 || ((gl_kind & clk_packed) != 0 && !TYPE_PACKED (to)))
1635 /* For the purposes of overload resolution, we ignore the fact
1636 this expression is a bitfield or packed field. (In particular,
1637 [over.ics.ref] says specifically that a function with a
1638 non-const reference parameter is viable even if the
1639 argument is a bitfield.)
1640
1641 However, when we actually call the function we must create
1642 a temporary to which to bind the reference. If the
1643 reference is volatile, or isn't const, then we cannot make
1644 a temporary, so we just issue an error when the conversion
1645 actually occurs. */
1646 conv->need_temporary_p = true;
1647
1648 /* Don't allow binding of lvalues (other than function lvalues) to
1649 rvalue references. */
1650 if (is_lvalue && TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto)
1651 && TREE_CODE (to) != FUNCTION_TYPE
1652 && !(flags & LOOKUP_PREFER_RVALUE))
1653 conv->bad_p = true;
1654
1655 /* Nor the reverse. */
1656 if (!is_lvalue && !TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto)
1657 && (!CP_TYPE_CONST_NON_VOLATILE_P (to)
1658 || (flags & LOOKUP_NO_RVAL_BIND))
1659 && TREE_CODE (to) != FUNCTION_TYPE)
1660 conv->bad_p = true;
1661
1662 if (!compatible_p)
1663 conv->bad_p = true;
1664
1665 return conv;
1666 }
1667 /* [class.conv.fct] A conversion function is never used to convert a
1668 (possibly cv-qualified) object to the (possibly cv-qualified) same
1669 object type (or a reference to it), to a (possibly cv-qualified) base
1670 class of that type (or a reference to it).... */
1671 else if (CLASS_TYPE_P (from) && !related_p
1672 && !(flags & LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION))
1673 {
1674 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1675
1676 If the initializer expression
1677
1678 -- has a class type (i.e., T2 is a class type) can be
1679 implicitly converted to an lvalue of type "cv3 T3," where
1680 "cv1 T1" is reference-compatible with "cv3 T3". (this
1681 conversion is selected by enumerating the applicable
1682 conversion functions (_over.match.ref_) and choosing the
1683 best one through overload resolution. (_over.match_).
1684
1685 the reference is bound to the lvalue result of the conversion
1686 in the second case. */
1687 z_candidate *cand = build_user_type_conversion_1 (rto, expr, flags,
1688 complain);
1689 if (cand)
1690 return cand->second_conv;
1691 }
1692
1693 /* From this point on, we conceptually need temporaries, even if we
1694 elide them. Only the cases above are "direct bindings". */
1695 if (flags & LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND)
1696 return NULL;
1697
1698 /* [over.ics.rank]
1699
1700 When a parameter of reference type is not bound directly to an
1701 argument expression, the conversion sequence is the one required
1702 to convert the argument expression to the underlying type of the
1703 reference according to _over.best.ics_. Conceptually, this
1704 conversion sequence corresponds to copy-initializing a temporary
1705 of the underlying type with the argument expression. Any
1706 difference in top-level cv-qualification is subsumed by the
1707 initialization itself and does not constitute a conversion. */
1708
1709 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1710
1711 Otherwise, the reference shall be an lvalue reference to a
1712 non-volatile const type, or the reference shall be an rvalue
1713 reference.
1714
1715 We try below to treat this as a bad conversion to improve diagnostics,
1716 but if TO is an incomplete class, we need to reject this conversion
1717 now to avoid unnecessary instantiation. */
1718 if (!CP_TYPE_CONST_NON_VOLATILE_P (to) && !TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto)
1719 && !COMPLETE_TYPE_P (to))
1720 return NULL;
1721
1722 /* We're generating a temporary now, but don't bind any more in the
1723 conversion (specifically, don't slice the temporary returned by a
1724 conversion operator). */
1725 flags |= LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND;
1726
1727 /* Core issue 899: When [copy-]initializing a temporary to be bound
1728 to the first parameter of a copy constructor (12.8) called with
1729 a single argument in the context of direct-initialization,
1730 explicit conversion functions are also considered.
1731
1732 So don't set LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING in that case. */
1733 if (!(flags & LOOKUP_COPY_PARM))
1734 flags |= LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING;
1735
1736 if (!conv)
1737 conv = implicit_conversion (to, from, expr, c_cast_p,
1738 flags, complain);
1739 if (!conv)
1740 return NULL;
1741
1742 if (conv->user_conv_p)
1743 {
1744 /* If initializing the temporary used a conversion function,
1745 recalculate the second conversion sequence. */
1746 for (conversion *t = conv; t; t = next_conversion (t))
1747 if (t->kind == ck_user
1748 && DECL_CONV_FN_P (t->cand->fn))
1749 {
1750 tree ftype = TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (t->cand->fn));
1751 int sflags = (flags|LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION)&~LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND;
1752 conversion *new_second
1753 = reference_binding (rto, ftype, NULL_TREE, c_cast_p,
1754 sflags, complain);
1755 if (!new_second)
1756 return NULL;
1757 return merge_conversion_sequences (t, new_second);
1758 }
1759 }
1760
1761 conv = build_conv (ck_ref_bind, rto, conv);
1762 /* This reference binding, unlike those above, requires the
1763 creation of a temporary. */
1764 conv->need_temporary_p = true;
1765 conv->rvaluedness_matches_p = TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto);
1766
1767 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1768
1769 Otherwise, the reference shall be an lvalue reference to a
1770 non-volatile const type, or the reference shall be an rvalue
1771 reference. */
1772 if (!CP_TYPE_CONST_NON_VOLATILE_P (to) && !TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (rto))
1773 conv->bad_p = true;
1774
1775 /* [dcl.init.ref]
1776
1777 Otherwise, a temporary of type "cv1 T1" is created and
1778 initialized from the initializer expression using the rules for a
1779 non-reference copy initialization. If T1 is reference-related to
1780 T2, cv1 must be the same cv-qualification as, or greater
1781 cv-qualification than, cv2; otherwise, the program is ill-formed. */
1782 if (related_p && !at_least_as_qualified_p (to, from))
1783 conv->bad_p = true;
1784
1785 return conv;
1786}
1787
1788/* Returns the implicit conversion sequence (see [over.ics]) from type
1789 FROM to type TO. The optional expression EXPR may affect the
1790 conversion. FLAGS are the usual overloading flags. If C_CAST_P is
1791 true, this conversion is coming from a C-style cast. */
1792
1793static conversion *
1794implicit_conversion (tree to, tree from, tree expr, bool c_cast_p,
1795 int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
1796{
1797 conversion *conv;
1798
1799 if (from == error_mark_node || to == error_mark_node
1800 || expr == error_mark_node)
1801 return NULL;
1802
1803 /* Other flags only apply to the primary function in overload
1804 resolution, or after we've chosen one. */
1805 flags &= (LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING|LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION|LOOKUP_COPY_PARM
1806 |LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND|LOOKUP_NO_RVAL_BIND|LOOKUP_PREFER_RVALUE
1807 |LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING|LOOKUP_PROTECT|LOOKUP_NO_NON_INTEGRAL);
1808
1809 /* FIXME: actually we don't want warnings either, but we can't just
1810 have 'complain &= ~(tf_warning|tf_error)' because it would cause
1811 the regression of, eg, g++.old-deja/g++.benjamin/16077.C.
1812 We really ought not to issue that warning until we've committed
1813 to that conversion. */
1814 complain &= ~tf_error;
1815
1816 /* Call reshape_init early to remove redundant braces. */
1817 if (expr && BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (expr)
1818 && CLASS_TYPE_P (to)
1819 && COMPLETE_TYPE_P (complete_type (to))
1820 && !CLASSTYPE_NON_AGGREGATE (to))
1821 {
1822 expr = reshape_init (to, expr, complain);
1823 if (expr == error_mark_node)
1824 return NULL;
1825 from = TREE_TYPE (expr);
1826 }
1827
1828 if (TREE_CODE (to) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
1829 conv = reference_binding (to, from, expr, c_cast_p, flags, complain);
1830 else
1831 conv = standard_conversion (to, from, expr, c_cast_p, flags, complain);
1832
1833 if (conv)
1834 return conv;
1835
1836 if (expr && BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (expr))
1837 {
1838 if (is_std_init_list (to))
1839 return build_list_conv (to, expr, flags, complain);
1840
1841 /* As an extension, allow list-initialization of _Complex. */
1842 if (TREE_CODE (to) == COMPLEX_TYPE)
1843 {
1844 conv = build_complex_conv (to, expr, flags, complain);
1845 if (conv)
1846 return conv;
1847 }
1848
1849 /* Allow conversion from an initializer-list with one element to a
1850 scalar type. */
1851 if (SCALAR_TYPE_P (to))
1852 {
1853 int nelts = CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (expr);
1854 tree elt;
1855
1856 if (nelts == 0)
1857 elt = build_value_init (to, tf_none);
1858 else if (nelts == 1)
1859 elt = CONSTRUCTOR_ELT (expr, 0)->value;
1860 else
1861 elt = error_mark_node;
1862
1863 conv = implicit_conversion (to, TREE_TYPE (elt), elt,
1864 c_cast_p, flags, complain);
1865 if (conv)
1866 {
1867 conv->check_narrowing = true;
1868 if (BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (elt))
1869 /* Too many levels of braces, i.e. '{{1}}'. */
1870 conv->bad_p = true;
1871 return conv;
1872 }
1873 }
1874 else if (TREE_CODE (to) == ARRAY_TYPE)
1875 return build_array_conv (to, expr, flags, complain);
1876 }
1877
1878 if (expr != NULL_TREE
1879 && (MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (from)
1880 || MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (to))
1881 && (flags & LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION) == 0)
1882 {
1883 struct z_candidate *cand;
1884
1885 if (CLASS_TYPE_P (to)
1886 && BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (expr)
1887 && !CLASSTYPE_NON_AGGREGATE (complete_type (to)))
1888 return build_aggr_conv (to, expr, flags, complain);
1889
1890 cand = build_user_type_conversion_1 (to, expr, flags, complain);
1891 if (cand)
1892 {
1893 if (BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (expr)
1894 && CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (expr) == 1
1895 && !is_list_ctor (cand->fn))
1896 {
1897 /* "If C is not an initializer-list constructor and the
1898 initializer list has a single element of type cv U, where U is
1899 X or a class derived from X, the implicit conversion sequence
1900 has Exact Match rank if U is X, or Conversion rank if U is
1901 derived from X." */
1902 tree elt = CONSTRUCTOR_ELT (expr, 0)->value;
1903 tree elttype = TREE_TYPE (elt);
1904 if (reference_related_p (to, elttype))
1905 return implicit_conversion (to, elttype, elt,
1906 c_cast_p, flags, complain);
1907 }
1908 conv = cand->second_conv;
1909 }
1910
1911 /* We used to try to bind a reference to a temporary here, but that
1912 is now handled after the recursive call to this function at the end
1913 of reference_binding. */
1914 return conv;
1915 }
1916
1917 return NULL;
1918}
1919
1920/* Add a new entry to the list of candidates. Used by the add_*_candidate
1921 functions. ARGS will not be changed until a single candidate is
1922 selected. */
1923
1924static struct z_candidate *
1925add_candidate (struct z_candidate **candidates,
1926 tree fn, tree first_arg, const vec<tree, va_gc> *args,
1927 size_t num_convs, conversion **convs,
1928 tree access_path, tree conversion_path,
1929 int viable, struct rejection_reason *reason,
1930 int flags)
1931{
1932 struct z_candidate *cand = (struct z_candidate *)
1933 conversion_obstack_alloc (sizeof (struct z_candidate));
1934
1935 cand->fn = fn;
1936 cand->first_arg = first_arg;
1937 cand->args = args;
1938 cand->convs = convs;
1939 cand->num_convs = num_convs;
1940 cand->access_path = access_path;
1941 cand->conversion_path = conversion_path;
1942 cand->viable = viable;
1943 cand->reason = reason;
1944 cand->next = *candidates;
1945 cand->flags = flags;
1946 *candidates = cand;
1947
1948 return cand;
1949}
1950
1951/* Return the number of remaining arguments in the parameter list
1952 beginning with ARG. */
1953
1954int
1955remaining_arguments (tree arg)
1956{
1957 int n;
1958
1959 for (n = 0; arg != NULL_TREE && arg != void_list_node;
1960 arg = TREE_CHAIN (arg))
1961 n++;
1962
1963 return n;
1964}
1965
1966/* Create an overload candidate for the function or method FN called
1967 with the argument list FIRST_ARG/ARGS and add it to CANDIDATES.
1968 FLAGS is passed on to implicit_conversion.
1969
1970 This does not change ARGS.
1971
1972 CTYPE, if non-NULL, is the type we want to pretend this function
1973 comes from for purposes of overload resolution. */
1974
1975static struct z_candidate *
1976add_function_candidate (struct z_candidate **candidates,
1977 tree fn, tree ctype, tree first_arg,
1978 const vec<tree, va_gc> *args, tree access_path,
1979 tree conversion_path, int flags,
1980 tsubst_flags_t complain)
1981{
1982 tree parmlist = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (TREE_TYPE (fn));
1983 int i, len;
1984 conversion **convs;
1985 tree parmnode;
1986 tree orig_first_arg = first_arg;
1987 int skip;
1988 int viable = 1;
1989 struct rejection_reason *reason = NULL;
1990
1991 /* At this point we should not see any functions which haven't been
1992 explicitly declared, except for friend functions which will have
1993 been found using argument dependent lookup. */
1994 gcc_assert (!DECL_ANTICIPATED (fn) || DECL_HIDDEN_FRIEND_P (fn));
1995
1996 /* The `this', `in_chrg' and VTT arguments to constructors are not
1997 considered in overload resolution. */
1998 if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
1999 {
2000 if (ctor_omit_inherited_parms (fn))
2001 /* Bring back parameters omitted from an inherited ctor. */
2002 parmlist = FUNCTION_FIRST_USER_PARMTYPE (DECL_ORIGIN (fn));
2003 else
2004 parmlist = skip_artificial_parms_for (fn, parmlist);
2005 skip = num_artificial_parms_for (fn);
2006 if (skip > 0 && first_arg != NULL_TREE)
2007 {
2008 --skip;
2009 first_arg = NULL_TREE;
2010 }
2011 }
2012 else
2013 skip = 0;
2014
2015 len = vec_safe_length (args) - skip + (first_arg != NULL_TREE ? 1 : 0);
2016 convs = alloc_conversions (len);
2017
2018 /* 13.3.2 - Viable functions [over.match.viable]
2019 First, to be a viable function, a candidate function shall have enough
2020 parameters to agree in number with the arguments in the list.
2021
2022 We need to check this first; otherwise, checking the ICSes might cause
2023 us to produce an ill-formed template instantiation. */
2024
2025 parmnode = parmlist;
2026 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
2027 {
2028 if (parmnode == NULL_TREE || parmnode == void_list_node)
2029 break;
2030 parmnode = TREE_CHAIN (parmnode);
2031 }
2032
2033 if ((i < len && parmnode)
2034 || !sufficient_parms_p (parmnode))
2035 {
2036 int remaining = remaining_arguments (parmnode);
2037 viable = 0;
2038 reason = arity_rejection (first_arg, i + remaining, len);
2039 }
2040
2041 /* An inherited constructor (12.6.3 [class.inhctor.init]) that has a first
2042 parameter of type "reference to cv C" (including such a constructor
2043 instantiated from a template) is excluded from the set of candidate
2044 functions when used to construct an object of type D with an argument list
2045 containing a single argument if C is reference-related to D. */
2046 if (viable && len == 1 && parmlist && DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn)
2047 && flag_new_inheriting_ctors
2048 && DECL_INHERITED_CTOR (fn))
2049 {
2050 tree ptype = non_reference (TREE_VALUE (parmlist));
2051 tree dtype = DECL_CONTEXT (fn);
2052 tree btype = DECL_INHERITED_CTOR_BASE (fn);
2053 if (reference_related_p (ptype, dtype)
2054 && reference_related_p (btype, ptype))
2055 {
2056 viable = false;
2057 reason = inherited_ctor_rejection ();
2058 }
2059 }
2060
2061 /* Second, for a function to be viable, its constraints must be
2062 satisfied. */
2063 if (flag_concepts && viable
2064 && !constraints_satisfied_p (fn))
2065 {
2066 reason = constraint_failure (fn);
2067 viable = false;
2068 }
2069
2070 /* When looking for a function from a subobject from an implicit
2071 copy/move constructor/operator=, don't consider anything that takes (a
2072 reference to) an unrelated type. See c++/44909 and core 1092. */
2073 if (viable && parmlist && (flags & LOOKUP_DEFAULTED))
2074 {
2075 if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
2076 i = 1;
2077 else if (DECL_ASSIGNMENT_OPERATOR_P (fn)
2078 && DECL_OVERLOADED_OPERATOR_P (fn) == NOP_EXPR)
2079 i = 2;
2080 else
2081 i = 0;
2082 if (i && len == i)
2083 {
2084 parmnode = chain_index (i-1, parmlist);
2085 if (!reference_related_p (non_reference (TREE_VALUE (parmnode)),
2086 ctype))
2087 viable = 0;
2088 }
2089
2090 /* This only applies at the top level. */
2091 flags &= ~LOOKUP_DEFAULTED;
2092 }
2093
2094 if (! viable)
2095 goto out;
2096
2097 /* Third, for F to be a viable function, there shall exist for each
2098 argument an implicit conversion sequence that converts that argument
2099 to the corresponding parameter of F. */
2100
2101 parmnode = parmlist;
2102
2103 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
2104 {
2105 tree argtype, to_type;
2106 tree arg;
2107 conversion *t;
2108 int is_this;
2109
2110 if (parmnode == void_list_node)
2111 break;
2112
2113 if (i == 0 && first_arg != NULL_TREE)
2114 arg = first_arg;
2115 else
2116 arg = CONST_CAST_TREE (
2117 (*args)[i + skip - (first_arg != NULL_TREE ? 1 : 0)]);
2118 argtype = lvalue_type (arg);
2119
2120 is_this = (i == 0 && DECL_NONSTATIC_MEMBER_FUNCTION_P (fn)
2121 && ! DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn));
2122
2123 if (parmnode)
2124 {
2125 tree parmtype = TREE_VALUE (parmnode);
2126 int lflags = flags;
2127
2128 parmnode = TREE_CHAIN (parmnode);
2129
2130 /* The type of the implicit object parameter ('this') for
2131 overload resolution is not always the same as for the
2132 function itself; conversion functions are considered to
2133 be members of the class being converted, and functions
2134 introduced by a using-declaration are considered to be
2135 members of the class that uses them.
2136
2137 Since build_over_call ignores the ICS for the `this'
2138 parameter, we can just change the parm type. */
2139 if (ctype && is_this)
2140 {
2141 parmtype = cp_build_qualified_type
2142 (ctype, cp_type_quals (TREE_TYPE (parmtype)));
2143 if (FUNCTION_REF_QUALIFIED (TREE_TYPE (fn)))
2144 {
2145 /* If the function has a ref-qualifier, the implicit
2146 object parameter has reference type. */
2147 bool rv = FUNCTION_RVALUE_QUALIFIED (TREE_TYPE (fn));
2148 parmtype = cp_build_reference_type (parmtype, rv);
2149 /* The special handling of 'this' conversions in compare_ics
2150 does not apply if there is a ref-qualifier. */
2151 is_this = false;
2152 }
2153 else
2154 {
2155 parmtype = build_pointer_type (parmtype);
2156 arg = build_this (arg);
2157 argtype = lvalue_type (arg);
2158 }
2159 }
2160
2161 /* Core issue 899: When [copy-]initializing a temporary to be bound
2162 to the first parameter of a copy constructor (12.8) called with
2163 a single argument in the context of direct-initialization,
2164 explicit conversion functions are also considered.
2165
2166 So set LOOKUP_COPY_PARM to let reference_binding know that
2167 it's being called in that context. We generalize the above
2168 to handle move constructors and template constructors as well;
2169 the standardese should soon be updated similarly. */
2170 if (ctype && i == 0 && (len-skip == 1)
2171 && DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn)
2172 && parmtype != error_mark_node
2173 && (same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p
2174 (non_reference (parmtype), ctype)))
2175 {
2176 if (!(flags & LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING))
2177 lflags |= LOOKUP_COPY_PARM;
2178 /* We allow user-defined conversions within init-lists, but
2179 don't list-initialize the copy parm, as that would mean
2180 using two levels of braces for the same type. */
2181 if ((flags & LOOKUP_LIST_INIT_CTOR)
2182 && BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (arg))
2183 lflags |= LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION;
2184 }
2185 else
2186 lflags |= LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING;
2187
2188 t = implicit_conversion (parmtype, argtype, arg,
2189 /*c_cast_p=*/false, lflags, complain);
2190 to_type = parmtype;
2191 }
2192 else
2193 {
2194 t = build_identity_conv (argtype, arg);
2195 t->ellipsis_p = true;
2196 to_type = argtype;
2197 }
2198
2199 if (t && is_this)
2200 t->this_p = true;
2201
2202 convs[i] = t;
2203 if (! t)
2204 {
2205 viable = 0;
2206 reason = arg_conversion_rejection (first_arg, i, argtype, to_type);
2207 break;
2208 }
2209
2210 if (t->bad_p)
2211 {
2212 viable = -1;
2213 reason = bad_arg_conversion_rejection (first_arg, i, arg, to_type);
2214 }
2215 }
2216
2217 out:
2218 return add_candidate (candidates, fn, orig_first_arg, args, len, convs,
2219 access_path, conversion_path, viable, reason, flags);
2220}
2221
2222/* Create an overload candidate for the conversion function FN which will
2223 be invoked for expression OBJ, producing a pointer-to-function which
2224 will in turn be called with the argument list FIRST_ARG/ARGLIST,
2225 and add it to CANDIDATES. This does not change ARGLIST. FLAGS is
2226 passed on to implicit_conversion.
2227
2228 Actually, we don't really care about FN; we care about the type it
2229 converts to. There may be multiple conversion functions that will
2230 convert to that type, and we rely on build_user_type_conversion_1 to
2231 choose the best one; so when we create our candidate, we record the type
2232 instead of the function. */
2233
2234static struct z_candidate *
2235add_conv_candidate (struct z_candidate **candidates, tree fn, tree obj,
2236 const vec<tree, va_gc> *arglist,
2237 tree access_path, tree conversion_path,
2238 tsubst_flags_t complain)
2239{
2240 tree totype = TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (fn));
2241 int i, len, viable, flags;
2242 tree parmlist, parmnode;
2243 conversion **convs;
2244 struct rejection_reason *reason;
2245
2246 for (parmlist = totype; TREE_CODE (parmlist) != FUNCTION_TYPE; )
2247 parmlist = TREE_TYPE (parmlist);
2248 parmlist = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (parmlist);
2249
2250 len = vec_safe_length (arglist) + 1;
2251 convs = alloc_conversions (len);
2252 parmnode = parmlist;
2253 viable = 1;
2254 flags = LOOKUP_IMPLICIT;
2255 reason = NULL;
2256
2257 /* Don't bother looking up the same type twice. */
2258 if (*candidates && (*candidates)->fn == totype)
2259 return NULL;
2260
2261 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
2262 {
2263 tree arg, argtype, convert_type = NULL_TREE;
2264 conversion *t;
2265
2266 if (i == 0)
2267 arg = obj;
2268 else
2269 arg = (*arglist)[i - 1];
2270 argtype = lvalue_type (arg);
2271
2272 if (i == 0)
2273 {
2274 t = build_identity_conv (argtype, NULL_TREE);
2275 t = build_conv (ck_user, totype, t);
2276 /* Leave the 'cand' field null; we'll figure out the conversion in
2277 convert_like_real if this candidate is chosen. */
2278 convert_type = totype;
2279 }
2280 else if (parmnode == void_list_node)
2281 break;
2282 else if (parmnode)
2283 {
2284 t = implicit_conversion (TREE_VALUE (parmnode), argtype, arg,
2285 /*c_cast_p=*/false, flags, complain);
2286 convert_type = TREE_VALUE (parmnode);
2287 }
2288 else
2289 {
2290 t = build_identity_conv (argtype, arg);
2291 t->ellipsis_p = true;
2292 convert_type = argtype;
2293 }
2294
2295 convs[i] = t;
2296 if (! t)
2297 break;
2298
2299 if (t->bad_p)
2300 {
2301 viable = -1;
2302 reason = bad_arg_conversion_rejection (NULL_TREE, i, arg, convert_type);
2303 }
2304
2305 if (i == 0)
2306 continue;
2307
2308 if (parmnode)
2309 parmnode = TREE_CHAIN (parmnode);
2310 }
2311
2312 if (i < len
2313 || ! sufficient_parms_p (parmnode))
2314 {
2315 int remaining = remaining_arguments (parmnode);
2316 viable = 0;
2317 reason = arity_rejection (NULL_TREE, i + remaining, len);
2318 }
2319
2320 return add_candidate (candidates, totype, obj, arglist, len, convs,
2321 access_path, conversion_path, viable, reason, flags);
2322}
2323
2324static void
2325build_builtin_candidate (struct z_candidate **candidates, tree fnname,
2326 tree type1, tree type2, tree *args, tree *argtypes,
2327 int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
2328{
2329 conversion *t;
2330 conversion **convs;
2331 size_t num_convs;
2332 int viable = 1, i;
2333 tree types[2];
2334 struct rejection_reason *reason = NULL;
2335
2336 types[0] = type1;
2337 types[1] = type2;
2338
2339 num_convs = args[2] ? 3 : (args[1] ? 2 : 1);
2340 convs = alloc_conversions (num_convs);
2341
2342 /* TRUTH_*_EXPR do "contextual conversion to bool", which means explicit
2343 conversion ops are allowed. We handle that here by just checking for
2344 boolean_type_node because other operators don't ask for it. COND_EXPR
2345 also does contextual conversion to bool for the first operand, but we
2346 handle that in build_conditional_expr, and type1 here is operand 2. */
2347 if (type1 != boolean_type_node)
2348 flags |= LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING;
2349
2350 for (i = 0; i < 2; ++i)
2351 {
2352 if (! args[i])
2353 break;
2354
2355 t = implicit_conversion (types[i], argtypes[i], args[i],
2356 /*c_cast_p=*/false, flags, complain);
2357 if (! t)
2358 {
2359 viable = 0;
2360 /* We need something for printing the candidate. */
2361 t = build_identity_conv (types[i], NULL_TREE);
2362 reason = arg_conversion_rejection (NULL_TREE, i, argtypes[i],
2363 types[i]);
2364 }
2365 else if (t->bad_p)
2366 {
2367 viable = 0;
2368 reason = bad_arg_conversion_rejection (NULL_TREE, i, args[i],
2369 types[i]);
2370 }
2371 convs[i] = t;
2372 }
2373
2374 /* For COND_EXPR we rearranged the arguments; undo that now. */
2375 if (args[2])
2376 {
2377 convs[2] = convs[1];
2378 convs[1] = convs[0];
2379 t = implicit_conversion (boolean_type_node, argtypes[2], args[2],
2380 /*c_cast_p=*/false, flags,
2381 complain);
2382 if (t)
2383 convs[0] = t;
2384 else
2385 {
2386 viable = 0;
2387 reason = arg_conversion_rejection (NULL_TREE, 0, argtypes[2],
2388 boolean_type_node);
2389 }
2390 }
2391
2392 add_candidate (candidates, fnname, /*first_arg=*/NULL_TREE, /*args=*/NULL,
2393 num_convs, convs,
2394 /*access_path=*/NULL_TREE,
2395 /*conversion_path=*/NULL_TREE,
2396 viable, reason, flags);
2397}
2398
2399static bool
2400is_complete (tree t)
2401{
2402 return COMPLETE_TYPE_P (complete_type (t));
2403}
2404
2405/* Returns nonzero if TYPE is a promoted arithmetic type. */
2406
2407static bool
2408promoted_arithmetic_type_p (tree type)
2409{
2410 /* [over.built]
2411
2412 In this section, the term promoted integral type is used to refer
2413 to those integral types which are preserved by integral promotion
2414 (including e.g. int and long but excluding e.g. char).
2415 Similarly, the term promoted arithmetic type refers to promoted
2416 integral types plus floating types. */
2417 return ((CP_INTEGRAL_TYPE_P (type)
2418 && same_type_p (type_promotes_to (type), type))
2419 || TREE_CODE (type) == REAL_TYPE);
2420}
2421
2422/* Create any builtin operator overload candidates for the operator in
2423 question given the converted operand types TYPE1 and TYPE2. The other
2424 args are passed through from add_builtin_candidates to
2425 build_builtin_candidate.
2426
2427 TYPE1 and TYPE2 may not be permissible, and we must filter them.
2428 If CODE is requires candidates operands of the same type of the kind
2429 of which TYPE1 and TYPE2 are, we add both candidates
2430 CODE (TYPE1, TYPE1) and CODE (TYPE2, TYPE2). */
2431
2432static void
2433add_builtin_candidate (struct z_candidate **candidates, enum tree_code code,
2434 enum tree_code code2, tree fnname, tree type1,
2435 tree type2, tree *args, tree *argtypes, int flags,
2436 tsubst_flags_t complain)
2437{
2438 switch (code)
2439 {
2440 case POSTINCREMENT_EXPR:
2441 case POSTDECREMENT_EXPR:
2442 args[1] = integer_zero_node;
2443 type2 = integer_type_node;
2444 break;
2445 default:
2446 break;
2447 }
2448
2449 switch (code)
2450 {
2451
2452/* 4 For every pair T, VQ), where T is an arithmetic or enumeration type,
2453 and VQ is either volatile or empty, there exist candidate operator
2454 functions of the form
2455 VQ T& operator++(VQ T&);
2456 T operator++(VQ T&, int);
2457 5 For every pair T, VQ), where T is an enumeration type or an arithmetic
2458 type other than bool, and VQ is either volatile or empty, there exist
2459 candidate operator functions of the form
2460 VQ T& operator--(VQ T&);
2461 T operator--(VQ T&, int);
2462 6 For every pair T, VQ), where T is a cv-qualified or cv-unqualified
2463 complete object type, and VQ is either volatile or empty, there exist
2464 candidate operator functions of the form
2465 T*VQ& operator++(T*VQ&);
2466 T*VQ& operator--(T*VQ&);
2467 T* operator++(T*VQ&, int);
2468 T* operator--(T*VQ&, int); */
2469
2470 case POSTDECREMENT_EXPR:
2471 case PREDECREMENT_EXPR:
2472 if (TREE_CODE (type1) == BOOLEAN_TYPE)
2473 return;
2474 /* FALLTHRU */
2475 case POSTINCREMENT_EXPR:
2476 case PREINCREMENT_EXPR:
2477 if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type1) || TYPE_PTROB_P (type1))
2478 {
2479 type1 = build_reference_type (type1);
2480 break;
2481 }
2482 return;
2483
2484/* 7 For every cv-qualified or cv-unqualified object type T, there
2485 exist candidate operator functions of the form
2486
2487 T& operator*(T*);
2488
2489 8 For every function type T, there exist candidate operator functions of
2490 the form
2491 T& operator*(T*); */
2492
2493 case INDIRECT_REF:
2494 if (TYPE_PTR_P (type1)
2495 && (TYPE_PTROB_P (type1)
2496 || TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (type1)) == FUNCTION_TYPE))
2497 break;
2498 return;
2499
2500/* 9 For every type T, there exist candidate operator functions of the form
2501 T* operator+(T*);
2502
2503 10For every promoted arithmetic type T, there exist candidate operator
2504 functions of the form
2505 T operator+(T);
2506 T operator-(T); */
2507
2508 case UNARY_PLUS_EXPR: /* unary + */
2509 if (TYPE_PTR_P (type1))
2510 break;
2511 /* FALLTHRU */
2512 case NEGATE_EXPR:
2513 if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type1))
2514 break;
2515 return;
2516
2517/* 11For every promoted integral type T, there exist candidate operator
2518 functions of the form
2519 T operator~(T); */
2520
2521 case BIT_NOT_EXPR:
2522 if (INTEGRAL_OR_UNSCOPED_ENUMERATION_TYPE_P (type1))
2523 break;
2524 return;
2525
2526/* 12For every quintuple C1, C2, T, CV1, CV2), where C2 is a class type, C1
2527 is the same type as C2 or is a derived class of C2, T is a complete
2528 object type or a function type, and CV1 and CV2 are cv-qualifier-seqs,
2529 there exist candidate operator functions of the form
2530 CV12 T& operator->*(CV1 C1*, CV2 T C2::*);
2531 where CV12 is the union of CV1 and CV2. */
2532
2533 case MEMBER_REF:
2534 if (TYPE_PTR_P (type1) && TYPE_PTRMEM_P (type2))
2535 {
2536 tree c1 = TREE_TYPE (type1);
2537 tree c2 = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (type2);
2538
2539 if (MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (c1) && DERIVED_FROM_P (c2, c1)
2540 && (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (type2)
2541 || is_complete (TYPE_PTRMEM_POINTED_TO_TYPE (type2))))
2542 break;
2543 }
2544 return;
2545
2546/* 13For every pair of promoted arithmetic types L and R, there exist can-
2547 didate operator functions of the form
2548 LR operator*(L, R);
2549 LR operator/(L, R);
2550 LR operator+(L, R);
2551 LR operator-(L, R);
2552 bool operator<(L, R);
2553 bool operator>(L, R);
2554 bool operator<=(L, R);
2555 bool operator>=(L, R);
2556 bool operator==(L, R);
2557 bool operator!=(L, R);
2558 where LR is the result of the usual arithmetic conversions between
2559 types L and R.
2560
2561 14For every pair of types T and I, where T is a cv-qualified or cv-
2562 unqualified complete object type and I is a promoted integral type,
2563 there exist candidate operator functions of the form
2564 T* operator+(T*, I);
2565 T& operator[](T*, I);
2566 T* operator-(T*, I);
2567 T* operator+(I, T*);
2568 T& operator[](I, T*);
2569
2570 15For every T, where T is a pointer to complete object type, there exist
2571 candidate operator functions of the form112)
2572 ptrdiff_t operator-(T, T);
2573
2574 16For every pointer or enumeration type T, there exist candidate operator
2575 functions of the form
2576 bool operator<(T, T);
2577 bool operator>(T, T);
2578 bool operator<=(T, T);
2579 bool operator>=(T, T);
2580 bool operator==(T, T);
2581 bool operator!=(T, T);
2582
2583 17For every pointer to member type T, there exist candidate operator
2584 functions of the form
2585 bool operator==(T, T);
2586 bool operator!=(T, T); */
2587
2588 case MINUS_EXPR:
2589 if (TYPE_PTROB_P (type1) && TYPE_PTROB_P (type2))
2590 break;
2591 if (TYPE_PTROB_P (type1)
2592 && INTEGRAL_OR_UNSCOPED_ENUMERATION_TYPE_P (type2))
2593 {
2594 type2 = ptrdiff_type_node;
2595 break;
2596 }
2597 /* FALLTHRU */
2598 case MULT_EXPR:
2599 case TRUNC_DIV_EXPR:
2600 if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type1) && ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type2))
2601 break;
2602 return;
2603
2604 case EQ_EXPR:
2605 case NE_EXPR:
2606 if ((TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (type1) && TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (type2))
2607 || (TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (type1) && TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (type2)))
2608 break;
2609 if (TYPE_PTRMEM_P (type1) && null_ptr_cst_p (args[1]))
2610 {
2611 type2 = type1;
2612 break;
2613 }
2614 if (TYPE_PTRMEM_P (type2) && null_ptr_cst_p (args[0]))
2615 {
2616 type1 = type2;
2617 break;
2618 }
2619 /* Fall through. */
2620 case LT_EXPR:
2621 case GT_EXPR:
2622 case LE_EXPR:
2623 case GE_EXPR:
2624 case MAX_EXPR:
2625 case MIN_EXPR:
2626 if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type1) && ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type2))
2627 break;
2628 if (TYPE_PTR_P (type1) && TYPE_PTR_P (type2))
2629 break;
2630 if (TREE_CODE (type1) == ENUMERAL_TYPE
2631 && TREE_CODE (type2) == ENUMERAL_TYPE)
2632 break;
2633 if (TYPE_PTR_P (type1)
2634 && null_ptr_cst_p (args[1]))
2635 {
2636 type2 = type1;
2637 break;
2638 }
2639 if (null_ptr_cst_p (args[0])
2640 && TYPE_PTR_P (type2))
2641 {
2642 type1 = type2;
2643 break;
2644 }
2645 return;
2646
2647 case PLUS_EXPR:
2648 if (ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type1) && ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (type2))
2649 break;
2650 /* FALLTHRU */
2651 case ARRAY_REF:
2652 if (INTEGRAL_OR_UNSCOPED_ENUMERATION_TYPE_P (type1) && TYPE_PTROB_P (type2))
2653 {
2654 type1 = ptrdiff_type_node;
2655 break;
2656 }
2657 if (TYPE_PTROB_P (type1) && INTEGRAL_OR_UNSCOPED_ENUMERATION_TYPE_P (type2))
2658 {
2659 type2 = ptrdiff_type_node;
2660 break;
2661 }
2662 return;
2663
2664/* 18For every pair of promoted integral types L and R, there exist candi-
2665 date operator functions of the form
2666 LR operator%(L, R);
2667 LR operator&(L, R);
2668 LR operator^(L, R);
2669 LR operator|(L, R);
2670 L operator<<(L, R);
2671 L operator>>(L, R);
