7564 tree expr, addr;
7565 tree return_type;
7566 const tree *argarray;
7567 unsigned int nargs;
7568
7569 if (undeduced_auto_decl (fn))
7570 mark_used (fn, complain);
7571 else
7572 /* Otherwise set TREE_USED for the benefit of -Wunused-function.
7573 See PR80598. */
7574 TREE_USED (fn) = 1;
7575
7576 return_type = TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (fn));
7577 nargs = vec_safe_length (args);
7578 if (first_arg == NULL_TREE)
7579 argarray = args->address ();
7580 else
7581 {
7582 tree *alcarray;
7583 unsigned int ix;
7584 tree arg;
7585
7586 ++nargs;
7587 alcarray = XALLOCAVEC (tree, nargs);
7588 alcarray[0] = build_this (first_arg);
7589 FOR_EACH_VEC_SAFE_ELT (args, ix, arg)
7590 alcarray[ix + 1] = arg;
7591 argarray = alcarray;
7592 }
7593
7594 addr = build_addr_func (fn, complain);
7595 if (addr == error_mark_node)
7596 return error_mark_node;
7597 expr = build_call_array_loc (input_location, return_type,
7598 addr, nargs, argarray);
7599 if (TREE_THIS_VOLATILE (fn) && cfun)
7600 current_function_returns_abnormally = 1;
7601 return convert_from_reference (expr);
7602 }
7603
7604 /* Give any warnings we noticed during overload resolution. */
7605 if (cand->warnings && (complain & tf_warning))
7606 {
7607 struct candidate_warning *w;
7608 for (w = cand->warnings; w; w = w->next)
7609 joust (cand, w->loser, 1, complain);
7610 }
7611
7612 /* OK, we're actually calling this inherited constructor; set its deletedness
7613 appropriately. We can get away with doing this here because calling is
7614 the only way to refer to a constructor. */
7615 if (DECL_INHERITED_CTOR (fn))
7616 deduce_inheriting_ctor (fn);
7617
7618 /* Make =delete work with SFINAE. */
7619 if (DECL_DELETED_FN (fn) && !(complain & tf_error))
7620 return error_mark_node;
7621
7622 if (DECL_FUNCTION_MEMBER_P (fn))
7623 {
7624 tree access_fn;
7625 /* If FN is a template function, two cases must be considered.
7626 For example:
7627
7628 struct A {
7629 protected:
7630 template <class T> void f();
7631 };
7632 template <class T> struct B {
7633 protected:
7634 void g();
7635 };
7636 struct C : A, B<int> {
7637 using A::f; // #1
7638 using B<int>::g; // #2
7639 };
7640
7641 In case #1 where `A::f' is a member template, DECL_ACCESS is
7642 recorded in the primary template but not in its specialization.
7643 We check access of FN using its primary template.
7644
7645 In case #2, where `B<int>::g' has a DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO simply
7646 because it is a member of class template B, DECL_ACCESS is
7647 recorded in the specialization `B<int>::g'. We cannot use its
7648 primary template because `B<T>::g' and `B<int>::g' may have
7649 different access. */
7650 if (DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO (fn)
7651 && DECL_MEMBER_TEMPLATE_P (DECL_TI_TEMPLATE (fn)))
7652 access_fn = DECL_TI_TEMPLATE (fn);
7653 else
7654 access_fn = fn;
7655 if (!perform_or_defer_access_check (cand->access_path, access_fn,
7656 fn, complain))
7657 return error_mark_node;
7658 }
7659
7660 /* If we're checking for implicit delete, don't bother with argument
7661 conversions. */
7662 if (flags & LOOKUP_SPECULATIVE)
7663 {
7664 if (DECL_DELETED_FN (fn))
7665 {
7666 if (complain & tf_error)
7667 mark_used (fn);
7668 return error_mark_node;
7669 }
7670 if (cand->viable == 1)
7671 return fn;
7672 else if (!(complain & tf_error))
7673 /* Reject bad conversions now. */
7674 return error_mark_node;
7675 /* else continue to get conversion error. */
7676 }
7677
7678 /* N3276 magic doesn't apply to nested calls. */
7679 tsubst_flags_t decltype_flag = (complain & tf_decltype);
7680 complain &= ~tf_decltype;
7681 /* No-Cleanup doesn't apply to nested calls either. */
7682 tsubst_flags_t no_cleanup_complain = complain;
7683 complain &= ~tf_no_cleanup;
7684
7685 /* Find maximum size of vector to hold converted arguments. */
7686 parmlen = list_length (parm);
7687 nargs = vec_safe_length (args) + (first_arg != NULL_TREE ? 1 : 0);
7688 if (parmlen > nargs)
7689 nargs = parmlen;
7690 argarray = XALLOCAVEC (tree, nargs);
7691
7692 /* The implicit parameters to a constructor are not considered by overload
7693 resolution, and must be of the proper type. */
7694 if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
7695 {
7696 tree object_arg;
7697 if (first_arg != NULL_TREE)
7698 {
7699 object_arg = first_arg;
7700 first_arg = NULL_TREE;
7701 }
7702 else
7703 {
7704 object_arg = (*args)[arg_index];
7705 ++arg_index;
7706 }
7707 argarray[j++] = build_this (object_arg);
7708 parm = TREE_CHAIN (parm);
7709 /* We should never try to call the abstract constructor. */
7710 gcc_assert (!DECL_HAS_IN_CHARGE_PARM_P (fn));
7711
7712 if (DECL_HAS_VTT_PARM_P (fn))
7713 {
7714 argarray[j++] = (*args)[arg_index];
7715 ++arg_index;
7716 parm = TREE_CHAIN (parm);
7717 }
7718 }
7719 /* Bypass access control for 'this' parameter. */
7720 else if (TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (fn)) == METHOD_TYPE)
7721 {
7722 tree parmtype = TREE_VALUE (parm);
7723 tree arg = build_this (first_arg != NULL_TREE
7724 ? first_arg
7725 : (*args)[arg_index]);
7726 tree argtype = TREE_TYPE (arg);
7727 tree converted_arg;
7728 tree base_binfo;
7729
7730 if (convs[i]->bad_p)
7731 {
7732 if (complain & tf_error)
7733 {
7734 if (permerror (input_location, "passing %qT as %<this%> "
7735 "argument discards qualifiers",
7736 TREE_TYPE (argtype)))
7737 inform (DECL_SOURCE_LOCATION (fn), " in call to %qD", fn);
7738 }
7739 else
7740 return error_mark_node;
7741 }
7742
7743 /* See if the function member or the whole class type is declared
7744 final and the call can be devirtualized. */
7745 if (DECL_FINAL_P (fn)
7746 || CLASSTYPE_FINAL (TYPE_METHOD_BASETYPE (TREE_TYPE (fn))))
7747 flags |= LOOKUP_NONVIRTUAL;
7748
7749 /* [class.mfct.nonstatic]: If a nonstatic member function of a class
7750 X is called for an object that is not of type X, or of a type
7751 derived from X, the behavior is undefined.
7752
7753 So we can assume that anything passed as 'this' is non-null, and
7754 optimize accordingly. */
7755 gcc_assert (TYPE_PTR_P (parmtype));
7756 /* Convert to the base in which the function was declared. */
7757 gcc_assert (cand->conversion_path != NULL_TREE);
7758 converted_arg = build_base_path (PLUS_EXPR,
7759 arg,
7760 cand->conversion_path,
7761 1, complain);
7762 /* Check that the base class is accessible. */
7763 if (!accessible_base_p (TREE_TYPE (argtype),
7764 BINFO_TYPE (cand->conversion_path), true))
7765 {
7766 if (complain & tf_error)
7767 error ("%qT is not an accessible base of %qT",
7768 BINFO_TYPE (cand->conversion_path),
7769 TREE_TYPE (argtype));
7770 else
7771 return error_mark_node;
7772 }
7773 /* If fn was found by a using declaration, the conversion path
7774 will be to the derived class, not the base declaring fn. We
7775 must convert from derived to base. */
7776 base_binfo = lookup_base (TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (converted_arg)),
7777 TREE_TYPE (parmtype), ba_unique,
7778 NULL, complain);
7779 converted_arg = build_base_path (PLUS_EXPR, converted_arg,
7780 base_binfo, 1, complain);
7781
7782 argarray[j++] = converted_arg;
7783 parm = TREE_CHAIN (parm);
7784 if (first_arg != NULL_TREE)
7785 first_arg = NULL_TREE;
7786 else
7787 ++arg_index;
7788 ++i;
7789 is_method = 1;
7790 }
7791
7792 gcc_assert (first_arg == NULL_TREE);
7793 for (; arg_index < vec_safe_length (args) && parm;
7794 parm = TREE_CHAIN (parm), ++arg_index, ++i)
7795 {
7796 tree type = TREE_VALUE (parm);
7797 tree arg = (*args)[arg_index];
7798 bool conversion_warning = true;
7799
7800 conv = convs[i];
7801
7802 /* If the argument is NULL and used to (implicitly) instantiate a
7803 template function (and bind one of the template arguments to
7804 the type of 'long int'), we don't want to warn about passing NULL
7805 to non-pointer argument.
7806 For example, if we have this template function:
7807
7808 template<typename T> void func(T x) {}
7809
7810 we want to warn (when -Wconversion is enabled) in this case:
7811
7812 void foo() {
7813 func<int>(NULL);
7814 }
7815
7816 but not in this case:
7817
7818 void foo() {
7819 func(NULL);
7820 }
7821 */
7822 if (arg == null_node
7823 && DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO (fn)
7824 && cand->template_decl
7825 && !(flags & LOOKUP_EXPLICIT_TMPL_ARGS))
7826 conversion_warning = false;
7827
7828 /* Warn about initializer_list deduction that isn't currently in the
7829 working draft. */
7830 if (cxx_dialect > cxx98
7831 && flag_deduce_init_list
7832 && cand->template_decl
7833 && is_std_init_list (non_reference (type))
7834 && BRACE_ENCLOSED_INITIALIZER_P (arg))
7835 {
7836 tree tmpl = TI_TEMPLATE (cand->template_decl);
7837 tree realparm = chain_index (j, DECL_ARGUMENTS (cand->fn));
7838 tree patparm = get_pattern_parm (realparm, tmpl);
7839 tree pattype = TREE_TYPE (patparm);
7840 if (PACK_EXPANSION_P (pattype))
7841 pattype = PACK_EXPANSION_PATTERN (pattype);
7842 pattype = non_reference (pattype);
7843
7844 if (TREE_CODE (pattype) == TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM
7845 && (cand->explicit_targs == NULL_TREE
7846 || (TREE_VEC_LENGTH (cand->explicit_targs)
7847 <= TEMPLATE_TYPE_IDX (pattype))))
7848 {
7849 pedwarn (input_location, 0, "deducing %qT as %qT",
7850 non_reference (TREE_TYPE (patparm)),
7851 non_reference (type));
7852 pedwarn (DECL_SOURCE_LOCATION (cand->fn), 0,
7853 " in call to %qD", cand->fn);
7854 pedwarn (input_location, 0,
7855 " (you can disable this with -fno-deduce-init-list)");
7856 }
7857 }
7858
7859 /* Set user_conv_p on the argument conversions, so rvalue/base handling
7860 knows not to allow any more UDCs. This needs to happen after we
7861 process cand->warnings. */
7862 if (flags & LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION)
7863 conv->user_conv_p = true;
7864
7865 tsubst_flags_t arg_complain = complain;
7866 if (!conversion_warning)
7867 arg_complain &= ~tf_warning;
7868
7869 val = convert_like_with_context (conv, arg, fn, i - is_method,
7870 arg_complain);
7871 val = convert_for_arg_passing (type, val, arg_complain);
7872
7873 if (val == error_mark_node)
7874 return error_mark_node;
7875 else
7876 argarray[j++] = val;
7877 }
7878
7879 /* Default arguments */
7880 for (; parm && parm != void_list_node; parm = TREE_CHAIN (parm), i++)
7881 {
7882 if (TREE_VALUE (parm) == error_mark_node)
7883 return error_mark_node;
7884 argarray[j++] = convert_default_arg (TREE_VALUE (parm),
7885 TREE_PURPOSE (parm),
7886 fn, i - is_method,
7887 complain);
7888 }
7889
7890 /* Ellipsis */
7891 int magic = magic_varargs_p (fn);
7892 for (; arg_index < vec_safe_length (args); ++arg_index)
7893 {
7894 tree a = (*args)[arg_index];
7895 if ((magic == 3 && arg_index == 2) || magic == 2)
7896 {
7897 /* Do no conversions for certain magic varargs. */
7898 a = mark_type_use (a);
7899 if (TREE_CODE (a) == FUNCTION_DECL && reject_gcc_builtin (a))
7900 return error_mark_node;
7901 }
7902 else if (magic != 0)
7903 /* For other magic varargs only do decay_conversion. */
7904 a = decay_conversion (a, complain);
7905 else if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn)
7906 && same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p (DECL_CONTEXT (fn),
7907 TREE_TYPE (a)))
7908 {
7909 /* Avoid infinite recursion trying to call A(...). */
7910 if (complain & tf_error)
7911 /* Try to call the actual copy constructor for a good error. */
7912 call_copy_ctor (a, complain);
7913 return error_mark_node;
7914 }
7915 else
7916 a = convert_arg_to_ellipsis (a, complain);
7917 if (a == error_mark_node)
7918 return error_mark_node;
7919 argarray[j++] = a;
7920 }
7921
7922 gcc_assert (j <= nargs);
7923 nargs = j;
7924
7925 /* Avoid to do argument-transformation, if warnings for format, and for
7926 nonnull are disabled. Just in case that at least one of them is active
7927 the check_function_arguments function might warn about something. */
7928
7929 bool warned_p = false;
7930 if (warn_nonnull
7931 || warn_format
7932 || warn_suggest_attribute_format
7933 || warn_restrict)
7934 {
7935 tree *fargs = (!nargs ? argarray
7936 : (tree *) alloca (nargs * sizeof (tree)));
7937 for (j = 0; j < nargs; j++)
7938 {
7939 /* For -Wformat undo the implicit passing by hidden reference
7940 done by convert_arg_to_ellipsis. */
7941 if (TREE_CODE (argarray[j]) == ADDR_EXPR
7942 && TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (argarray[j])) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
7943 fargs[j] = TREE_OPERAND (argarray[j], 0);
7944 else
7945 fargs[j] = maybe_constant_value (argarray[j]);
7946 }
7947
7948 warned_p = check_function_arguments (input_location, fn, TREE_TYPE (fn),
7949 nargs, fargs);
7950 }
7951
7952 if (DECL_INHERITED_CTOR (fn))
7953 {
7954 /* Check for passing ellipsis arguments to an inherited constructor. We
7955 could handle this by open-coding the inherited constructor rather than
7956 defining it, but let's not bother now. */
7957 if (!cp_unevaluated_operand
7958 && cand->num_convs
7959 && cand->convs[cand->num_convs-1]->ellipsis_p)
7960 {
7961 if (complain & tf_error)
7962 {
7963 sorry ("passing arguments to ellipsis of inherited constructor "
7964 "%qD", cand->fn);
7965 inform (DECL_SOURCE_LOCATION (cand->fn), "declared here");
7966 }
7967 return error_mark_node;
7968 }
7969
7970 /* A base constructor inheriting from a virtual base doesn't get the
7971 inherited arguments, just this and __vtt. */
7972 if (ctor_omit_inherited_parms (fn))
7973 nargs = 2;
7974 }
7975
7976 /* Avoid actually calling copy constructors and copy assignment operators,
7977 if possible. */
7978
7979 if (! flag_elide_constructors)
7980 /* Do things the hard way. */;
7981 else if (cand->num_convs == 1
7982 && (DECL_COPY_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn)
7983 || DECL_MOVE_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
7984 /* It's unsafe to elide the constructor when handling
7985 a noexcept-expression, it may evaluate to the wrong
7986 value (c++/53025). */
7987 && cp_noexcept_operand == 0)
7988 {
7989 tree targ;
7990 tree arg = argarray[num_artificial_parms_for (fn)];
7991 tree fa;
7992 bool trivial = trivial_fn_p (fn);
7993
7994 /* Pull out the real argument, disregarding const-correctness. */
7995 targ = arg;
7996 /* Strip the reference binding for the constructor parameter. */
7997 if (CONVERT_EXPR_P (targ)
7998 && TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (targ)) == REFERENCE_TYPE)
7999 targ = TREE_OPERAND (targ, 0);
8000 /* But don't strip any other reference bindings; binding a temporary to a
8001 reference prevents copy elision. */
8002 while ((CONVERT_EXPR_P (targ)
8003 && TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (targ)) != REFERENCE_TYPE)
8004 || TREE_CODE (targ) == NON_LVALUE_EXPR)
8005 targ = TREE_OPERAND (targ, 0);
8006 if (TREE_CODE (targ) == ADDR_EXPR)
8007 {
8008 targ = TREE_OPERAND (targ, 0);
8009 if (!same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p
8010 (TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (arg)), TREE_TYPE (targ)))
8011 targ = NULL_TREE;
8012 }
8013 else
8014 targ = NULL_TREE;
8015
8016 if (targ)
8017 arg = targ;
8018 else
8019 arg = cp_build_indirect_ref (arg, RO_NULL, complain);
8020
8021 /* In C++17 we shouldn't be copying a TARGET_EXPR except into a base
8022 subobject. */
8023 if (CHECKING_P && cxx_dialect >= cxx1z)
8024 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (arg) != TARGET_EXPR
8025 /* It's from binding the ref parm to a packed field. */
8026 || convs[0]->need_temporary_p
8027 || seen_error ()
8028 /* See unsafe_copy_elision_p. */
8029 || DECL_BASE_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn));
8030
8031 /* [class.copy]: the copy constructor is implicitly defined even if
8032 the implementation elided its use. */
8033 if (!trivial || DECL_DELETED_FN (fn))
8034 {
8035 if (!mark_used (fn, complain) && !(complain & tf_error))
8036 return error_mark_node;
8037 already_used = true;
8038 }
8039
8040 /* If we're creating a temp and we already have one, don't create a
8041 new one. If we're not creating a temp but we get one, use
8042 INIT_EXPR to collapse the temp into our target. Otherwise, if the
8043 ctor is trivial, do a bitwise copy with a simple TARGET_EXPR for a
8044 temp or an INIT_EXPR otherwise. */
8045 fa = argarray[0];
8046 if (is_dummy_object (fa))
8047 {
8048 if (TREE_CODE (arg) == TARGET_EXPR)
8049 return arg;
8050 else if (trivial)
8051 return force_target_expr (DECL_CONTEXT (fn), arg, complain);
8052 }
8053 else if ((trivial || TREE_CODE (arg) == TARGET_EXPR)
8054 && !unsafe_copy_elision_p (fa, arg))
8055 {
8056 tree to = cp_stabilize_reference (cp_build_indirect_ref (fa,
8057 RO_NULL,
8058 complain));
8059
8060 val = build2 (INIT_EXPR, DECL_CONTEXT (fn), to, arg);
8061 return val;
8062 }
8063 }
8064 else if (DECL_OVERLOADED_OPERATOR_P (fn) == NOP_EXPR
8065 && trivial_fn_p (fn)
8066 && !DECL_DELETED_FN (fn))
8067 {
8068 tree to = cp_stabilize_reference
8069 (cp_build_indirect_ref (argarray[0], RO_NULL, complain));
8070 tree type = TREE_TYPE (to);
8071 tree as_base = CLASSTYPE_AS_BASE (type);
8072 tree arg = argarray[1];
8073
8074 if (is_really_empty_class (type))
8075 {
8076 /* Avoid copying empty classes. */
8077 val = build2 (COMPOUND_EXPR, type, arg, to);
8078 TREE_NO_WARNING (val) = 1;
8079 }
8080 else if (tree_int_cst_equal (TYPE_SIZE (type), TYPE_SIZE (as_base)))
8081 {
8082 arg = cp_build_indirect_ref (arg, RO_NULL, complain);
8083 val = build2 (MODIFY_EXPR, TREE_TYPE (to), to, arg);
8084 /* Handle NSDMI that refer to the object being initialized. */
8085 replace_placeholders (arg, to);
8086 }
8087 else
8088 {
8089 /* We must only copy the non-tail padding parts. */
8090 tree arg0, arg2, t;
8091 tree array_type, alias_set;
8092
8093 arg2 = TYPE_SIZE_UNIT (as_base);
8094 arg0 = cp_build_addr_expr (to, complain);
8095
8096 array_type = build_array_type (unsigned_char_type_node,
8097 build_index_type
8098 (size_binop (MINUS_EXPR,
8099 arg2, size_int (1))));
8100 alias_set = build_int_cst (build_pointer_type (type), 0);
8101 t = build2 (MODIFY_EXPR, void_type_node,
8102 build2 (MEM_REF, array_type, arg0, alias_set),
8103 build2 (MEM_REF, array_type, arg, alias_set));
8104 val = build2 (COMPOUND_EXPR, TREE_TYPE (to), t, to);
8105 TREE_NO_WARNING (val) = 1;
8106 }
8107
8108 return val;
8109 }
8110 else if (!DECL_DELETED_FN (fn)
8111 && trivial_fn_p (fn))
8112 {
8113 if (DECL_DESTRUCTOR_P (fn))
8114 return fold_convert (void_type_node, argarray[0]);
8115 else if (default_ctor_p (fn))
8116 {
8117 if (is_dummy_object (argarray[0]))
8118 return force_target_expr (DECL_CONTEXT (fn), void_node,
8119 no_cleanup_complain);
8120 else
8121 return cp_build_indirect_ref (argarray[0], RO_NULL, complain);
8122 }
8123 }
8124
8125 /* For calls to a multi-versioned function, overload resolution
8126 returns the function with the highest target priority, that is,
8127 the version that will checked for dispatching first. If this
8128 version is inlinable, a direct call to this version can be made
8129 otherwise the call should go through the dispatcher. */
8130
8131 if (DECL_FUNCTION_VERSIONED (fn)
8132 && (current_function_decl == NULL
8133 || !targetm.target_option.can_inline_p (current_function_decl, fn)))
8134 {
8135 fn = get_function_version_dispatcher (fn);
8136 if (fn == NULL)
8137 return NULL;
8138 if (!already_used)
8139 mark_versions_used (fn);
8140 }
8141
8142 if (!already_used
8143 && !mark_used (fn, complain))
8144 return error_mark_node;
8145
8146 if (DECL_VINDEX (fn) && (flags & LOOKUP_NONVIRTUAL) == 0
8147 /* Don't mess with virtual lookup in instantiate_non_dependent_expr;
8148 virtual functions can't be constexpr. */
8149 && !in_template_function ())
8150 {
8151 tree t;
8152 tree binfo = lookup_base (TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (argarray[0])),
8153 DECL_CONTEXT (fn),
8154 ba_any, NULL, complain);
8155 gcc_assert (binfo && binfo != error_mark_node);
8156
8157 argarray[0] = build_base_path (PLUS_EXPR, argarray[0], binfo, 1,
8158 complain);
8159 if (TREE_SIDE_EFFECTS (argarray[0]))
8160 argarray[0] = save_expr (argarray[0]);
8161 t = build_pointer_type (TREE_TYPE (fn));
8162 fn = build_vfn_ref (argarray[0], DECL_VINDEX (fn));
8163 TREE_TYPE (fn) = t;
8164 }
8165 else
8166 {
8167 fn = build_addr_func (fn, complain);
8168 if (fn == error_mark_node)
8169 return error_mark_node;
8170 }
8171
8172 tree call = build_cxx_call (fn, nargs, argarray, complain|decltype_flag);
8173 if (call == error_mark_node)
8174 return call;
8175 if (cand->flags & LOOKUP_LIST_INIT_CTOR)
8176 {
8177 tree c = extract_call_expr (call);
8178 /* build_new_op_1 will clear this when appropriate. */
8179 CALL_EXPR_ORDERED_ARGS (c) = true;
8180 }
8181 if (warned_p)
8182 {
8183 tree c = extract_call_expr (call);
8184 if (TREE_CODE (c) == CALL_EXPR)
8185 TREE_NO_WARNING (c) = 1;
8186 }
8187 return call;
8188}
8189
8190/* Build and return a call to FN, using NARGS arguments in ARGARRAY.
8191 This function performs no overload resolution, conversion, or other
8192 high-level operations. */
8193
8194tree
8195build_cxx_call (tree fn, int nargs, tree *argarray,
8196 tsubst_flags_t complain)
8197{
8198 tree fndecl;
8199
8200 /* Remember roughly where this call is. */
8201 location_t loc = EXPR_LOC_OR_LOC (fn, input_location);
8202 fn = build_call_a (fn, nargs, argarray);
8203 SET_EXPR_LOCATION (fn, loc);
8204
8205 fndecl = get_callee_fndecl (fn);
8206
8207 /* Check that arguments to builtin functions match the expectations. */
8208 if (fndecl
8209 && DECL_BUILT_IN (fndecl)
8210 && DECL_BUILT_IN_CLASS (fndecl) == BUILT_IN_NORMAL)
8211 {
8212 int i;
8213
8214 /* We need to take care that values to BUILT_IN_NORMAL
8215 are reduced. */
8216 for (i = 0; i < nargs; i++)
8217 argarray[i] = fold_non_dependent_expr (argarray[i]);
8218
8219 if (!check_builtin_function_arguments (EXPR_LOCATION (fn), vNULL, fndecl,
8220 nargs, argarray))
8221 return error_mark_node;
8222 }
8223
8224 /* If it is a built-in array notation function, then the return type of
8225 the function is the element type of the array passed in as array
8226 notation (i.e. the first parameter of the function). */
8227 if (flag_cilkplus && TREE_CODE (fn) == CALL_EXPR)
8228 {
8229 enum built_in_function bif =
8230 is_cilkplus_reduce_builtin (CALL_EXPR_FN (fn));
8231 if (bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_ADD
8232 || bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_MUL
8233 || bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_MAX
8234 || bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_MIN
8235 || bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE
8236 || bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_MUTATING)
8237 {
8238 if (call_expr_nargs (fn) == 0)
8239 {
8240 error_at (EXPR_LOCATION (fn), "Invalid builtin arguments");
8241 return error_mark_node;
8242 }
8243 /* for bif == BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_ALL_ZERO or
8244 BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_ANY_ZERO or
8245 BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_ANY_NONZERO or
8246 BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_ALL_NONZERO or
8247 BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_MIN_IND or
8248 BUILT_IN_CILKPLUS_SEC_REDUCE_MAX_IND
8249 The pre-defined return-type is the correct one. */
8250 tree array_ntn = CALL_EXPR_ARG (fn, 0);
8251 TREE_TYPE (fn) = TREE_TYPE (array_ntn);
8252 return fn;
8253 }
8254 }
8255
8256 if (VOID_TYPE_P (TREE_TYPE (fn)))
8257 return fn;
8258
8259 /* 5.2.2/11: If a function call is a prvalue of object type: if the
8260 function call is either the operand of a decltype-specifier or the
8261 right operand of a comma operator that is the operand of a
8262 decltype-specifier, a temporary object is not introduced for the
8263 prvalue. The type of the prvalue may be incomplete. */
8264 if (!(complain & tf_decltype))
8265 {
8266 fn = require_complete_type_sfinae (fn, complain);
8267 if (fn == error_mark_node)
8268 return error_mark_node;
8269
8270 if (MAYBE_CLASS_TYPE_P (TREE_TYPE (fn)))
8271 fn = build_cplus_new (TREE_TYPE (fn), fn, complain);
8272 }
8273 return convert_from_reference (fn);
8274}
8275
8276/* Returns the value to use for the in-charge parameter when making a
8277 call to a function with the indicated NAME.
8278
8279 FIXME:Can't we find a neater way to do this mapping? */
8280
8281tree
8282in_charge_arg_for_name (tree name)
8283{
8284 if (name == base_ctor_identifier
8285 || name == base_dtor_identifier)
8286 return integer_zero_node;
8287 else if (name == complete_ctor_identifier)
8288 return integer_one_node;
8289 else if (name == complete_dtor_identifier)
8290 return integer_two_node;
8291 else if (name == deleting_dtor_identifier)
8292 return integer_three_node;
8293
8294 /* This function should only be called with one of the names listed
8295 above. */
8296 gcc_unreachable ();
8297 return NULL_TREE;
8298}
8299
8300/* We've built up a constructor call RET. Complain if it delegates to the
8301 constructor we're currently compiling. */
8302
8303static void
8304check_self_delegation (tree ret)
8305{
8306 if (TREE_CODE (ret) == TARGET_EXPR)
8307 ret = TARGET_EXPR_INITIAL (ret);
8308 tree fn = cp_get_callee_fndecl (ret);
8309 if (fn && DECL_ABSTRACT_ORIGIN (fn) == current_function_decl)
8310 error ("constructor delegates to itself");
8311}
8312
8313/* Build a call to a constructor, destructor, or an assignment
8314 operator for INSTANCE, an expression with class type. NAME
8315 indicates the special member function to call; *ARGS are the
8316 arguments. ARGS may be NULL. This may change ARGS. BINFO
8317 indicates the base of INSTANCE that is to be passed as the `this'
8318 parameter to the member function called.
8319
8320 FLAGS are the LOOKUP_* flags to use when processing the call.
8321
8322 If NAME indicates a complete object constructor, INSTANCE may be
8323 NULL_TREE. In this case, the caller will call build_cplus_new to
8324 store the newly constructed object into a VAR_DECL. */
8325
8326tree
8327build_special_member_call (tree instance, tree name, vec<tree, va_gc> **args,
8328 tree binfo, int flags, tsubst_flags_t complain)
8329{
8330 tree fns;
8331 /* The type of the subobject to be constructed or destroyed. */
8332 tree class_type;
8333 vec<tree, va_gc> *allocated = NULL;
8334 tree ret;
8335
8336 gcc_assert (name == complete_ctor_identifier
8337 || name == base_ctor_identifier
8338 || name == complete_dtor_identifier
8339 || name == base_dtor_identifier
8340 || name == deleting_dtor_identifier
8341 || name == cp_assignment_operator_id (NOP_EXPR));
8342 if (TYPE_P (binfo))
8343 {
8344 /* Resolve the name. */
8345 if (!complete_type_or_maybe_complain (binfo, NULL_TREE, complain))
8346 return error_mark_node;
8347
8348 binfo = TYPE_BINFO (binfo);
8349 }
8350
8351 gcc_assert (binfo != NULL_TREE);
8352
8353 class_type = BINFO_TYPE (binfo);
8354
8355 /* Handle the special case where INSTANCE is NULL_TREE. */
8356 if (name == complete_ctor_identifier && !instance)
8357 instance = build_dummy_object (class_type);
8358 else
8359 {
8360 if (name == complete_dtor_identifier
8361 || name == base_dtor_identifier
8362 || name == deleting_dtor_identifier)
8363 gcc_assert (args == NULL || vec_safe_is_empty (*args));
8364
8365 /* Convert to the base class, if necessary. */
8366 if (!same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p
8367 (TREE_TYPE (instance), BINFO_TYPE (binfo)))
8368 {
8369 if (name != cp_assignment_operator_id (NOP_EXPR))
8370 /* For constructors and destructors, either the base is
8371 non-virtual, or it is virtual but we are doing the
8372 conversion from a constructor or destructor for the
8373 complete object. In either case, we can convert
8374 statically. */
8375 instance = convert_to_base_statically (instance, binfo);
8376 else
8377 /* However, for assignment operators, we must convert
8378 dynamically if the base is virtual. */
8379 instance = build_base_path (PLUS_EXPR, instance,
8380 binfo, /*nonnull=*/1, complain);
8381 }
8382 }
8383
8384 gcc_assert (instance != NULL_TREE);
8385
8386 /* In C++17, "If the initializer expression is a prvalue and the
8387 cv-unqualified version of the source type is the same class as the class
8388 of the destination, the initializer expression is used to initialize the
8389 destination object." Handle that here to avoid doing overload
8390 resolution. */
8391 if (cxx_dialect >= cxx1z
8392 && args && vec_safe_length (*args) == 1
8393 && name == complete_ctor_identifier)
8394 {
8395 tree arg = (**args)[0];
8396
8397 /* FIXME P0135 doesn't say how to handle direct initialization from a
8398 type with a suitable conversion operator. Let's handle it like
8399 copy-initialization, but allowing explict conversions. */
8400 tsubst_flags_t sub_complain = tf_warning;
8401 if (!is_dummy_object (instance))
8402 /* If we're using this to initialize a non-temporary object, don't
8403 require the destructor to be accessible. */
8404 sub_complain |= tf_no_cleanup;
8405 if (!reference_related_p (class_type, TREE_TYPE (arg)))
8406 arg = perform_implicit_conversion_flags (class_type, arg,
8407 sub_complain,
8408 flags);
8409 if ((TREE_CODE (arg) == TARGET_EXPR
8410 || TREE_CODE (arg) == CONSTRUCTOR)
8411 && (same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p
8412 (class_type, TREE_TYPE (arg))))
8413 {
8414 if (is_dummy_object (instance))
8415 return arg;
8416 else if (TREE_CODE (arg) == TARGET_EXPR)
8417 TARGET_EXPR_DIRECT_INIT_P (arg) = true;
8418
8419 if ((complain & tf_error)
8420 && (flags & LOOKUP_DELEGATING_CONS))
8421 check_self_delegation (arg);
8422 /* Avoid change of behavior on Wunused-var-2.C. */
8423 mark_lvalue_use (instance);
8424 return build2 (INIT_EXPR, class_type, instance, arg);
8425 }
8426 }
8427
8428 fns = lookup_fnfields (binfo, name, 1);
8429
8430 /* When making a call to a constructor or destructor for a subobject
8431 that uses virtual base classes, pass down a pointer to a VTT for
8432 the subobject. */
8433 if ((name == base_ctor_identifier
8434 || name == base_dtor_identifier)
8435 && CLASSTYPE_VBASECLASSES (class_type))
8436 {
8437 tree vtt;
8438 tree sub_vtt;
8439
8440 /* If the current function is a complete object constructor
8441 or destructor, then we fetch the VTT directly.
8442 Otherwise, we look it up using the VTT we were given. */
8443 vtt = DECL_CHAIN (CLASSTYPE_VTABLES (current_class_type));
8444 vtt = decay_conversion (vtt, complain);
8445 if (vtt == error_mark_node)
8446 return error_mark_node;
8447 vtt = build_if_in_charge (vtt, current_vtt_parm);
8448 if (BINFO_SUBVTT_INDEX (binfo))
8449 sub_vtt = fold_build_pointer_plus (vtt, BINFO_SUBVTT_INDEX (binfo));
8450 else
8451 sub_vtt = vtt;
8452
8453 if (args == NULL)
8454 {
8455 allocated = make_tree_vector ();
8456 args = &allocated;
8457 }
8458
8459 vec_safe_insert (*args, 0, sub_vtt);
8460 }
8461
8462 ret = build_new_method_call (instance, fns, args,
8463 TYPE_BINFO (BINFO_TYPE (binfo)),
8464 flags, /*fn=*/NULL,
8465 complain);
8466
8467 if (allocated != NULL)
8468 release_tree_vector (allocated);
8469
8470 if ((complain & tf_error)
8471 && (flags & LOOKUP_DELEGATING_CONS)
8472 && name == complete_ctor_identifier)
8473 check_self_delegation (ret);
8474
8475 return ret;
8476}
8477
8478/* Return the NAME, as a C string. The NAME indicates a function that
8479 is a member of TYPE. *FREE_P is set to true if the caller must
8480 free the memory returned.
8481
8482 Rather than go through all of this, we should simply set the names
8483 of constructors and destructors appropriately, and dispense with
8484 ctor_identifier, dtor_identifier, etc. */
8485
8486static char *
8487name_as_c_string (tree name, tree type, bool *free_p)
8488{
8489 char *pretty_name;
8490
8491 /* Assume that we will not allocate memory. */
8492 *free_p = false;
8493 /* Constructors and destructors are special. */
8494 if (IDENTIFIER_CTOR_OR_DTOR_P (name))
8495 {
8496 pretty_name
8497 = CONST_CAST (char *, identifier_to_locale (IDENTIFIER_POINTER (constructor_name (type))));
8498 /* For a destructor, add the '~'. */
8499 if (name == complete_dtor_identifier
8500 || name == base_dtor_identifier
8501 || name == deleting_dtor_identifier)
8502 {
8503 pretty_name = concat ("~", pretty_name, NULL);
8504 /* Remember that we need to free the memory allocated. */
8505 *free_p = true;
8506 }
8507 }
8508 else if (IDENTIFIER_TYPENAME_P (name))
8509 {
8510 pretty_name = concat ("operator ",
8511 type_as_string_translate (TREE_TYPE (name),
8512 TFF_PLAIN_IDENTIFIER),
8513 NULL);
8514 /* Remember that we need to free the memory allocated. */
8515 *free_p = true;
8516 }
8517 else
8518 pretty_name = CONST_CAST (char *, identifier_to_locale (IDENTIFIER_POINTER (name)));
8519
8520 return pretty_name;
8521}
8522
8523/* Build a call to "INSTANCE.FN (ARGS)". If FN_P is non-NULL, it will
8524 be set, upon return, to the function called. ARGS may be NULL.
8525 This may change ARGS. */
8526
8527static tree
8528build_new_method_call_1 (tree instance, tree fns, vec<tree, va_gc> **args,
8529 tree conversion_path, int flags,
8530 tree *fn_p, tsubst_flags_t complain)
8531{
8532 struct z_candidate *candidates = 0, *cand;
8533 tree explicit_targs = NULL_TREE;
8534 tree basetype = NULL_TREE;
8535 tree access_binfo, binfo;
8536 tree optype;
8537 tree first_mem_arg = NULL_TREE;
8538 tree name;
8539 bool skip_first_for_error;
8540 vec<tree, va_gc> *user_args;
8541 tree call;
8542 tree fn;
8543 int template_only = 0;
8544 bool any_viable_p;
8545 tree orig_instance;
8546 tree orig_fns;
8547 vec<tree, va_gc> *orig_args = NULL;
8548 void *p;
8549
8550 gcc_assert (instance != NULL_TREE);
8551
8552 /* We don't know what function we're going to call, yet. */
8553 if (fn_p)
8554 *fn_p = NULL_TREE;
8555
8556 if (error_operand_p (instance)
8557 || !fns || error_operand_p (fns))
8558 return error_mark_node;
8559
8560 if (!BASELINK_P (fns))
8561 {
8562 if (complain & tf_error)
8563 error ("call to non-function %qD", fns);
8564 return error_mark_node;
8565 }
8566
8567 orig_instance = instance;
8568 orig_fns = fns;
8569
8570 /* Dismantle the baselink to collect all the information we need. */
8571 if (!conversion_path)
8572 conversion_path = BASELINK_BINFO (fns);
8573 access_binfo = BASELINK_ACCESS_BINFO (fns);
8574 binfo = BASELINK_BINFO (fns);
8575 optype = BASELINK_OPTYPE (fns);
8576 fns = BASELINK_FUNCTIONS (fns);
8577 if (TREE_CODE (fns) == TEMPLATE_ID_EXPR)
8578 {
8579 explicit_targs = TREE_OPERAND (fns, 1);
8580 fns = TREE_OPERAND (fns, 0);
8581 template_only = 1;
8582 }
8583 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (fns) == FUNCTION_DECL
8584 || TREE_CODE (fns) == TEMPLATE_DECL
8585 || TREE_CODE (fns) == OVERLOAD);
8586 fn = get_first_fn (fns);
8587 name = DECL_NAME (fn);
8588
8589 basetype = TYPE_MAIN_VARIANT (TREE_TYPE (instance));
8590 gcc_assert (CLASS_TYPE_P (basetype));
8591
8592 if (processing_template_decl)
8593 {
8594 orig_args = args == NULL ? NULL : make_tree_vector_copy (*args);
8595 instance = build_non_dependent_expr (instance);
8596 if (args != NULL)
8597 make_args_non_dependent (*args);
8598 }
8599
8600 user_args = args == NULL ? NULL : *args;
8601 /* Under DR 147 A::A() is an invalid constructor call,
8602 not a functional cast. */
8603 if (DECL_MAYBE_IN_CHARGE_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
8604 {
8605 if (! (complain & tf_error))
8606 return error_mark_node;
8607
8608 if (permerror (input_location,
8609 "cannot call constructor %<%T::%D%> directly",
8610 basetype, name))
8611 inform (input_location, "for a function-style cast, remove the "
8612 "redundant %<::%D%>", name);
8613 call = build_functional_cast (basetype, build_tree_list_vec (user_args),
8614 complain);
8615 return call;
8616 }
8617
8618 /* Figure out whether to skip the first argument for the error
8619 message we will display to users if an error occurs. We don't
8620 want to display any compiler-generated arguments. The "this"
8621 pointer hasn't been added yet. However, we must remove the VTT
8622 pointer if this is a call to a base-class constructor or
8623 destructor. */
8624 skip_first_for_error = false;
8625 if (IDENTIFIER_CTOR_OR_DTOR_P (name))
8626 {
8627 /* Callers should explicitly indicate whether they want to construct
8628 the complete object or just the part without virtual bases. */
8629 gcc_assert (name != ctor_identifier);
8630 /* Similarly for destructors. */
8631 gcc_assert (name != dtor_identifier);
8632 /* Remove the VTT pointer, if present. */
8633 if ((name == base_ctor_identifier || name == base_dtor_identifier)
8634 && CLASSTYPE_VBASECLASSES (basetype))
8635 skip_first_for_error = true;
8636 }
8637
8638 /* Process the argument list. */
8639 if (args != NULL && *args != NULL)
8640 {
8641 *args = resolve_args (*args, complain);
8642 if (*args == NULL)
8643 return error_mark_node;
8644 }
8645
8646 /* Consider the object argument to be used even if we end up selecting a
8647 static member function. */
8648 instance = mark_type_use (instance);
8649
8650 /* It's OK to call destructors and constructors on cv-qualified objects.
8651 Therefore, convert the INSTANCE to the unqualified type, if
8652 necessary. */
8653 if (DECL_DESTRUCTOR_P (fn)
8654 || DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
8655 {
8656 if (!same_type_p (basetype, TREE_TYPE (instance)))
8657 {
8658 instance = build_this (instance);
8659 instance = build_nop (build_pointer_type (basetype), instance);
8660 instance = build_fold_indirect_ref (instance);
8661 }
8662 }
8663 if (DECL_DESTRUCTOR_P (fn))
8664 name = complete_dtor_identifier;
8665
8666 /* For the overload resolution we need to find the actual `this`
8667 that would be captured if the call turns out to be to a
8668 non-static member function. Do not actually capture it at this
8669 point. */
8670 if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn))
8671 /* Constructors don't use the enclosing 'this'. */
8672 first_mem_arg = instance;
8673 else
8674 first_mem_arg = maybe_resolve_dummy (instance, false);
8675
8676 /* Get the high-water mark for the CONVERSION_OBSTACK. */
8677 p = conversion_obstack_alloc (0);
8678
8679 /* The number of arguments artificial parms in ARGS; we subtract one because
8680 there's no 'this' in ARGS. */
8681 unsigned skip = num_artificial_parms_for (fn) - 1;
8682
8683 /* If CONSTRUCTOR_IS_DIRECT_INIT is set, this was a T{ } form
8684 initializer, not T({ }). */
8685 if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn)
8686 && vec_safe_length (user_args) > skip
8687 && DIRECT_LIST_INIT_P ((*user_args)[skip]))
8688 {
8689 tree init_list = (*user_args)[skip];
8690 tree init = NULL_TREE;
8691
8692 gcc_assert (user_args->length () == skip + 1
8693 && !(flags & LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING));
8694
8695 /* If the initializer list has no elements and T is a class type with
8696 a default constructor, the object is value-initialized. Handle
8697 this here so we don't need to handle it wherever we use
8698 build_special_member_call. */
8699 if (CONSTRUCTOR_NELTS (init_list) == 0
8700 && TYPE_HAS_DEFAULT_CONSTRUCTOR (basetype)
8701 /* For a user-provided default constructor, use the normal
8702 mechanisms so that protected access works. */
8703 && type_has_non_user_provided_default_constructor (basetype)
8704 && !processing_template_decl)
8705 init = build_value_init (basetype, complain);
8706
8707 /* If BASETYPE is an aggregate, we need to do aggregate
8708 initialization. */
8709 else if (CP_AGGREGATE_TYPE_P (basetype))
8710 {
8711 init = reshape_init (basetype, init_list, complain);
8712 init = digest_init (basetype, init, complain);
8713 }
8714
8715 if (init)
8716 {
8717 if (is_dummy_object (instance))
8718 return get_target_expr_sfinae (init, complain);
8719 init = build2 (INIT_EXPR, TREE_TYPE (instance), instance, init);
8720 TREE_SIDE_EFFECTS (init) = true;
8721 return init;
8722 }
8723
8724 /* Otherwise go ahead with overload resolution. */
8725 add_list_candidates (fns, first_mem_arg, user_args,
8726 basetype, explicit_targs, template_only,
8727 conversion_path, access_binfo, flags,
8728 &candidates, complain);
8729 }
8730 else
8731 {
8732 add_candidates (fns, first_mem_arg, user_args, optype,
8733 explicit_targs, template_only, conversion_path,
8734 access_binfo, flags, &candidates, complain);
8735 }
8736 any_viable_p = false;
8737 candidates = splice_viable (candidates, false, &any_viable_p);
8738
8739 if (!any_viable_p)
8740 {
8741 if (complain & tf_error)
8742 {
8743 if (!COMPLETE_OR_OPEN_TYPE_P (basetype))
8744 cxx_incomplete_type_error (instance, basetype);
8745 else if (optype)
8746 error ("no matching function for call to %<%T::operator %T(%A)%#V%>",
8747 basetype, optype, build_tree_list_vec (user_args),
8748 TREE_TYPE (instance));
8749 else
8750 {
8751 tree arglist = build_tree_list_vec (user_args);
8752 tree errname = name;
8753 if (IDENTIFIER_CTOR_OR_DTOR_P (errname))
8754 {
8755 tree fn = DECL_ORIGIN (get_first_fn (fns));
8756 errname = DECL_NAME (fn);
8757 }
8758 if (explicit_targs)
8759 errname = lookup_template_function (errname, explicit_targs);
8760 if (skip_first_for_error)
8761 arglist = TREE_CHAIN (arglist);
8762 error ("no matching function for call to %<%T::%E(%A)%#V%>",
8763 basetype, errname, arglist,
8764 TREE_TYPE (instance));
8765 }
8766 print_z_candidates (location_of (name), candidates);
8767 }
8768 call = error_mark_node;
8769 }
8770 else
8771 {
8772 cand = tourney (candidates, complain);
8773 if (cand == 0)
8774 {
8775 char *pretty_name;
8776 bool free_p;
8777 tree arglist;
8778
8779 if (complain & tf_error)
8780 {
8781 pretty_name = name_as_c_string (name, basetype, &free_p);
8782 arglist = build_tree_list_vec (user_args);
8783 if (skip_first_for_error)
8784 arglist = TREE_CHAIN (arglist);
8785 if (!any_strictly_viable (candidates))
8786 error ("no matching function for call to %<%s(%A)%>",
8787 pretty_name, arglist);
8788 else
8789 error ("call of overloaded %<%s(%A)%> is ambiguous",
8790 pretty_name, arglist);
8791 print_z_candidates (location_of (name), candidates);
8792 if (free_p)
8793 free (pretty_name);
8794 }
8795 call = error_mark_node;
8796 }
8797 else
8798 {
8799 fn = cand->fn;
8800 call = NULL_TREE;
8801
8802 if (!(flags & LOOKUP_NONVIRTUAL)
8803 && DECL_PURE_VIRTUAL_P (fn)
8804 && instance == current_class_ref
8805 && (complain & tf_warning))
8806 {
8807 /* This is not an error, it is runtime undefined
8808 behavior. */
8809 if (!current_function_decl)
8810 warning (0, "pure virtual %q#D called from "
8811 "non-static data member initializer", fn);
8812 else if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (current_function_decl)
8813 || DECL_DESTRUCTOR_P (current_function_decl))
8814 warning (0, (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (current_function_decl)
8815 ? G_("pure virtual %q#D called from constructor")
8816 : G_("pure virtual %q#D called from destructor")),
8817 fn);
8818 }
8819
8820 if (TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (fn)) == METHOD_TYPE
8821 && !DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (fn)
8822 && is_dummy_object (instance))
8823 {
8824 instance = maybe_resolve_dummy (instance, true);
8825 if (instance == error_mark_node)
8826 call = error_mark_node;
8827 else if (!is_dummy_object (instance))
8828 {
8829 /* We captured 'this' in the current lambda now that
8830 we know we really need it. */
8831 cand->first_arg = instance;
8832 }
8833 else if (any_dependent_bases_p ())
8834 /* We can't tell until instantiation time whether we can use
8835 *this as the implicit object argument. */;
8836 else
8837 {
8838 if (complain & tf_error)
8839 error ("cannot call member function %qD without object",
8840 fn);
8841 call = error_mark_node;
8842 }
8843 }
8844
8845 if (call != error_mark_node)
8846 {
8847 /* Optimize away vtable lookup if we know that this
8848 function can't be overridden. We need to check if
8849 the context and the type where we found fn are the same,
8850 actually FN might be defined in a different class
8851 type because of a using-declaration. In this case, we
8852 do not want to perform a non-virtual call. */
8853 if (DECL_VINDEX (fn) && ! (flags & LOOKUP_NONVIRTUAL)
8854 && same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p
8855 (DECL_CONTEXT (fn), BINFO_TYPE (binfo))
8856 && resolves_to_fixed_type_p (instance, 0))
8857 flags |= LOOKUP_NONVIRTUAL;
8858 if (explicit_targs)
8859 flags |= LOOKUP_EXPLICIT_TMPL_ARGS;
8860 /* Now we know what function is being called. */
8861 if (fn_p)
8862 *fn_p = fn;
8863 /* Build the actual CALL_EXPR. */
8864 call = build_over_call (cand, flags, complain);
8865 /* In an expression of the form `a->f()' where `f' turns
8866 out to be a static member function, `a' is
8867 none-the-less evaluated. */
8868 if (TREE_CODE (TREE_TYPE (fn)) != METHOD_TYPE
8869 && !is_dummy_object (instance)
8870 && TREE_SIDE_EFFECTS (instance))
8871 {
8872 /* But avoid the implicit lvalue-rvalue conversion when 'a'
8873 is volatile. */
8874 tree a = instance;
8875 if (TREE_THIS_VOLATILE (a))
8876 a = build_this (a);
8877 call = build2 (COMPOUND_EXPR, TREE_TYPE (call), a, call);
8878 }
8879 else if (call != error_mark_node
8880 && DECL_DESTRUCTOR_P (cand->fn)
8881 && !VOID_TYPE_P (TREE_TYPE (call)))
8882 /* An explicit call of the form "x->~X()" has type
8883 "void". However, on platforms where destructors
8884 return "this" (i.e., those where
8885 targetm.cxx.cdtor_returns_this is true), such calls
8886 will appear to have a return value of pointer type
8887 to the low-level call machinery. We do not want to
8888 change the low-level machinery, since we want to be
8889 able to optimize "delete f()" on such platforms as
8890 "operator delete(~X(f()))" (rather than generating
8891 "t = f(), ~X(t), operator delete (t)"). */
8892 call = build_nop (void_type_node, call);
8893 }
8894 }
8895 }
8896
8897 if (processing_template_decl && call != error_mark_node)
8898 {
8899 bool cast_to_void = false;
8900
8901 if (TREE_CODE (call) == COMPOUND_EXPR)
8902 call = TREE_OPERAND (call, 1);
8903 else if (TREE_CODE (call) == NOP_EXPR)
8904 {
8905 cast_to_void = true;
8906 call = TREE_OPERAND (call, 0);
8907 }
8908 if (INDIRECT_REF_P (call))
8909 call = TREE_OPERAND (call, 0);
8910 call = (build_min_non_dep_call_vec
8911 (call,
8912 build_min (COMPONENT_REF, TREE_TYPE (CALL_EXPR_FN (call)),
8913 orig_instance, orig_fns, NULL_TREE),
8914 orig_args));
8915 SET_EXPR_LOCATION (call, input_location);
8916 call = convert_from_reference (call);
8917 if (cast_to_void)
8918 call = build_nop (void_type_node, call);
8919 }
8920
8921 /* Free all the conversions we allocated. */
8922 obstack_free (&conversion_obstack, p);
8923
8924 if (orig_args != NULL)
8925 release_tree_vector (orig_args);
8926
8927 return call;
8928}
8929
8930/* Wrapper for above. */
8931
8932tree
8933build_new_method_call (tree instance, tree fns, vec<tree, va_gc> **args,
8934 tree conversion_path, int flags,
8935 tree *fn_p, tsubst_flags_t complain)
8936{
8937 tree ret;
8938 bool subtime = timevar_cond_start (TV_OVERLOAD);
8939 ret = build_new_method_call_1 (instance, fns, args, conversion_path, flags,
8940 fn_p, complain);
8941 timevar_cond_stop (TV_OVERLOAD, subtime);
8942 return ret;
8943}
8944
8945/* Returns true iff standard conversion sequence ICS1 is a proper
8946 subsequence of ICS2. */
8947
8948static bool
8949is_subseq (conversion *ics1, conversion *ics2)
8950{
8951 /* We can assume that a conversion of the same code
8952 between the same types indicates a subsequence since we only get
8953 here if the types we are converting from are the same. */
8954
8955 while (ics1->kind == ck_rvalue
8956 || ics1->kind == ck_lvalue)
8957 ics1 = next_conversion (ics1);
8958
8959 while (1)
8960 {
8961 while (ics2->kind == ck_rvalue
8962 || ics2->kind == ck_lvalue)
8963 ics2 = next_conversion (ics2);
8964
8965 if (ics2->kind == ck_user
8966 || ics2->kind == ck_ambig
8967 || ics2->kind == ck_aggr
8968 || ics2->kind == ck_list
8969 || ics2->kind == ck_identity)
8970 /* At this point, ICS1 cannot be a proper subsequence of
8971 ICS2. We can get a USER_CONV when we are comparing the
8972 second standard conversion sequence of two user conversion
8973 sequences. */
8974 return false;
8975
8976 ics2 = next_conversion (ics2);
8977
8978 while (ics2->kind == ck_rvalue
8979 || ics2->kind == ck_lvalue)
8980 ics2 = next_conversion (ics2);
8981
8982 if (ics2->kind == ics1->kind
8983 && same_type_p (ics2->type, ics1->type)
8984 && (ics1->kind == ck_identity
8985 || same_type_p (next_conversion (ics2)->type,
8986 next_conversion (ics1)->type)))
8987 return true;
8988 }
8989}
8990
8991/* Returns nonzero iff DERIVED is derived from BASE. The inputs may
8992 be any _TYPE nodes. */
8993
8994bool
8995is_properly_derived_from (tree derived, tree base)
8996{
8997 if (!CLASS_TYPE_P (derived) || !CLASS_TYPE_P (base))
8998 return false;
8999
9000 /* We only allow proper derivation here. The DERIVED_FROM_P macro
9001 considers every class derived from itself. */
9002 return (!same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p (derived, base)
9003 && DERIVED_FROM_P (base, derived));
9004}
9005
9006/* We build the ICS for an implicit object parameter as a pointer
9007 conversion sequence. However, such a sequence should be compared
9008 as if it were a reference conversion sequence. If ICS is the
9009 implicit conversion sequence for an implicit object parameter,
9010 modify it accordingly. */
9011
9012static void
9013maybe_handle_implicit_object (conversion **ics)
9014{
9015 if ((*ics)->this_p)
9016 {
9017 /* [over.match.funcs]
9018
9019 For non-static member functions, the type of the
9020 implicit object parameter is "reference to cv X"
9021 where X is the class of which the function is a
9022 member and cv is the cv-qualification on the member
9023 function declaration. */
9024 conversion *t = *ics;
9025 tree reference_type;
9026
9027 /* The `this' parameter is a pointer to a class type. Make the
9028 implicit conversion talk about a reference to that same class
9029 type. */
9030 reference_type = TREE_TYPE (t->type);
9031 reference_type = build_reference_type (reference_type);
9032
9033 if (t->kind == ck_qual)
9034 t = next_conversion (t);
9035 if (t->kind == ck_ptr)
9036 t = next_conversion (t);
9037 t = build_identity_conv (TREE_TYPE (t->type), NULL_TREE);
9038 t = direct_reference_binding (reference_type, t);
9039 t->this_p = 1;
9040 t->rvaluedness_matches_p = 0;
9041 *ics = t;
9042 }
9043}
9044
9045/* If *ICS is a REF_BIND set *ICS to the remainder of the conversion,
9046 and return the initial reference binding conversion. Otherwise,
9047 leave *ICS unchanged and return NULL. */
9048
9049static conversion *
9050maybe_handle_ref_bind (conversion **ics)
9051{
9052 if ((*ics)->kind == ck_ref_bind)
9053 {
9054 conversion *old_ics = *ics;
9055 *ics = next_conversion (old_ics);
9056 (*ics)->user_conv_p = old_ics->user_conv_p;
9057 return old_ics;
9058 }
9059
9060 return NULL;
9061}
9062
9063/* Compare two implicit conversion sequences according to the rules set out in
9064 [over.ics.rank]. Return values:
9065
9066 1: ics1 is better than ics2
9067 -1: ics2 is better than ics1
9068 0: ics1 and ics2 are indistinguishable */
9069
9070static int
9071compare_ics (conversion *ics1, conversion *ics2)
9072{
9073 tree from_type1;
9074 tree from_type2;
9075 tree to_type1;
9076 tree to_type2;
9077 tree deref_from_type1 = NULL_TREE;
9078 tree deref_from_type2 = NULL_TREE;
9079 tree deref_to_type1 = NULL_TREE;
9080 tree deref_to_type2 = NULL_TREE;
9081 conversion_rank rank1, rank2;
9082
9083 /* REF_BINDING is nonzero if the result of the conversion sequence
9084 is a reference type. In that case REF_CONV is the reference
9085 binding conversion. */
9086 conversion *ref_conv1;
9087 conversion *ref_conv2;
9088
9089 /* Compare badness before stripping the reference conversion. */
9090 if (ics1->bad_p > ics2->bad_p)
9091 return -1;
9092 else if (ics1->bad_p < ics2->bad_p)
9093 return 1;
9094
9095 /* Handle implicit object parameters. */
9096 maybe_handle_implicit_object (&ics1);
9097 maybe_handle_implicit_object (&ics2);
9098
9099 /* Handle reference parameters. */
9100 ref_conv1 = maybe_handle_ref_bind (&ics1);
9101 ref_conv2 = maybe_handle_ref_bind (&ics2);
9102
9103 /* List-initialization sequence L1 is a better conversion sequence than
9104 list-initialization sequence L2 if L1 converts to
9105 std::initializer_list<X> for some X and L2 does not. */
9106 if (ics1->kind == ck_list && ics2->kind != ck_list)
9107 return 1;
9108 if (ics2->kind == ck_list && ics1->kind != ck_list)
9109 return -1;
9110
9111 /* [over.ics.rank]
9112
9113 When comparing the basic forms of implicit conversion sequences (as
9114 defined in _over.best.ics_)
9115
9116 --a standard conversion sequence (_over.ics.scs_) is a better
9117 conversion sequence than a user-defined conversion sequence
9118 or an ellipsis conversion sequence, and
9119
9120 --a user-defined conversion sequence (_over.ics.user_) is a
9121 better conversion sequence than an ellipsis conversion sequence
9122 (_over.ics.ellipsis_). */
9123 /* Use BAD_CONVERSION_RANK because we already checked for a badness
9124 mismatch. If both ICS are bad, we try to make a decision based on
9125 what would have happened if they'd been good. This is not an
9126 extension, we'll still give an error when we build up the call; this
9127 just helps us give a more helpful error message. */
9128 rank1 = BAD_CONVERSION_RANK (ics1);
9129 rank2 = BAD_CONVERSION_RANK (ics2);
9130
9131 if (rank1 > rank2)
9132 return -1;
9133 else if (rank1 < rank2)
9134 return 1;
9135
9136 if (ics1->ellipsis_p)
9137 /* Both conversions are ellipsis conversions. */
9138 return 0;
9139
9140 /* User-defined conversion sequence U1 is a better conversion sequence
9141 than another user-defined conversion sequence U2 if they contain the
9142 same user-defined conversion operator or constructor and if the sec-
9143 ond standard conversion sequence of U1 is better than the second
9144 standard conversion sequence of U2. */
9145
9146 /* Handle list-conversion with the same code even though it isn't always
9147 ranked as a user-defined conversion and it doesn't have a second
9148 standard conversion sequence; it will still have the desired effect.
9149 Specifically, we need to do the reference binding comparison at the
9150 end of this function. */
9151
9152 if (ics1->user_conv_p || ics1->kind == ck_list || ics1->kind == ck_aggr)
9153 {
9154 conversion *t1;
9155 conversion *t2;
9156
9157 for (t1 = ics1; t1->kind != ck_user; t1 = next_conversion (t1))
9158 if (t1->kind == ck_ambig || t1->kind == ck_aggr
9159 || t1->kind == ck_list)
9160 break;
9161 for (t2 = ics2; t2->kind != ck_user; t2 = next_conversion (t2))
9162 if (t2->kind == ck_ambig || t2->kind == ck_aggr
9163 || t2->kind == ck_list)
9164 break;
9165
9166 if (t1->kind != t2->kind)
9167 return 0;
9168 else if (t1->kind == ck_user)
9169 {
9170 tree f1 = t1->cand ? t1->cand->fn : t1->type;
9171 tree f2 = t2->cand ? t2->cand->fn : t2->type;
9172 if (f1 != f2)
9173 return 0;
9174 }
9175 else
9176 {
9177 /* For ambiguous or aggregate conversions, use the target type as
9178 a proxy for the conversion function. */
9179 if (!same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p (t1->type, t2->type))
9180 return 0;
9181 }
9182
9183 /* We can just fall through here, after setting up
9184 FROM_TYPE1 and FROM_TYPE2. */
9185 from_type1 = t1->type;
9186 from_type2 = t2->type;
9187 }
9188 else
9189 {
9190 conversion *t1;
9191 conversion *t2;
9192
9193 /* We're dealing with two standard conversion sequences.
9194
9195 [over.ics.rank]
9196
9197 Standard conversion sequence S1 is a better conversion
9198 sequence than standard conversion sequence S2 if
9199
9200 --S1 is a proper subsequence of S2 (comparing the conversion
9201 sequences in the canonical form defined by _over.ics.scs_,
9202 excluding any Lvalue Transformation; the identity
9203 conversion sequence is considered to be a subsequence of
9204 any non-identity conversion sequence */
9205
9206 t1 = ics1;
9207 while (t1->kind != ck_identity)
9208 t1 = next_conversion (t1);
9209 from_type1 = t1->type;
9210
9211 t2 = ics2;
9212 while (t2->kind != ck_identity)
9213 t2 = next_conversion (t2);
9214 from_type2 = t2->type;
9215 }
9216
9217 /* One sequence can only be a subsequence of the other if they start with
9218 the same type. They can start with different types when comparing the
9219 second standard conversion sequence in two user-defined conversion
9220 sequences. */
9221 if (same_type_p (from_type1, from_type2))
9222 {
9223 if (is_subseq (ics1, ics2))
9224 return 1;
9225 if (is_subseq (ics2, ics1))
9226 return -1;
9227 }
9228
9229 /* [over.ics.rank]
9230
9231 Or, if not that,
9232
9233 --the rank of S1 is better than the rank of S2 (by the rules
9234 defined below):
9235
9236 Standard conversion sequences are ordered by their ranks: an Exact
9237 Match is a better conversion than a Promotion, which is a better
9238 conversion than a Conversion.
9239
9240 Two conversion sequences with the same rank are indistinguishable
9241 unless one of the following rules applies:
9242
9243 --A conversion that does not a convert a pointer, pointer to member,
9244 or std::nullptr_t to bool is better than one that does.
9245
9246 The ICS_STD_RANK automatically handles the pointer-to-bool rule,
9247 so that we do not have to check it explicitly. */
9248 if (ics1->rank < ics2->rank)
9249 return 1;
9250 else if (ics2->rank < ics1->rank)
9251 return -1;
9252
9253 to_type1 = ics1->type;
9254 to_type2 = ics2->type;
9255
9256 /* A conversion from scalar arithmetic type to complex is worse than a
9257 conversion between scalar arithmetic types. */
9258 if (same_type_p (from_type1, from_type2)
9259 && ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (from_type1)
9260 && ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (to_type1)
9261 && ARITHMETIC_TYPE_P (to_type2)
9262 && ((TREE_CODE (to_type1) == COMPLEX_TYPE)
9263 != (TREE_CODE (to_type2) == COMPLEX_TYPE)))
9264 {
9265 if (TREE_CODE (to_type1) == COMPLEX_TYPE)
9266 return -1;
9267 else
9268 return 1;
9269 }
9270
9271 if (TYPE_PTR_P (from_type1)
9272 && TYPE_PTR_P (from_type2)
9273 && TYPE_PTR_P (to_type1)
9274 && TYPE_PTR_P (to_type2))
9275 {
9276 deref_from_type1 = TREE_TYPE (from_type1);
9277 deref_from_type2 = TREE_TYPE (from_type2);
9278 deref_to_type1 = TREE_TYPE (to_type1);
9279 deref_to_type2 = TREE_TYPE (to_type2);
9280 }
9281 /* The rules for pointers to members A::* are just like the rules
9282 for pointers A*, except opposite: if B is derived from A then
9283 A::* converts to B::*, not vice versa. For that reason, we
9284 switch the from_ and to_ variables here. */
9285 else if ((TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (from_type1) && TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (from_type2)
9286 && TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (to_type1) && TYPE_PTRDATAMEM_P (to_type2))
9287 || (TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (from_type1)
9288 && TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (from_type2)
9289 && TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (to_type1)
9290 && TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_P (to_type2)))
9291 {
9292 deref_to_type1 = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (from_type1);
9293 deref_to_type2 = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (from_type2);
9294 deref_from_type1 = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (to_type1);
9295 deref_from_type2 = TYPE_PTRMEM_CLASS_TYPE (to_type2);
9296 }
9297
9298 if (deref_from_type1 != NULL_TREE
9299 && RECORD_OR_UNION_CODE_P (TREE_CODE (deref_from_type1))
9300 && RECORD_OR_UNION_CODE_P (TREE_CODE (deref_from_type2)))
9301 {
9302 /* This was one of the pointer or pointer-like conversions.
9303
9304 [over.ics.rank]
9305
9306 --If class B is derived directly or indirectly from class A,
9307 conversion of B* to A* is better than conversion of B* to
9308 void*, and conversion of A* to void* is better than
9309 conversion of B* to void*. */
9310 if (VOID_TYPE_P (deref_to_type1)
9311 && VOID_TYPE_P (deref_to_type2))
9312 {
9313 if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_from_type1,
9314 deref_from_type2))
9315 return -1;
9316 else if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_from_type2,
9317 deref_from_type1))
9318 return 1;
9319 }
9320 else if (VOID_TYPE_P (deref_to_type1)
9321 || VOID_TYPE_P (deref_to_type2))
9322 {
9323 if (same_type_p (deref_from_type1, deref_from_type2))
9324 {
9325 if (VOID_TYPE_P (deref_to_type2))
9326 {
9327 if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_from_type1,
9328 deref_to_type1))
9329 return 1;
9330 }
9331 /* We know that DEREF_TO_TYPE1 is `void' here. */
9332 else if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_from_type1,
9333 deref_to_type2))
9334 return -1;
9335 }
9336 }
9337 else if (RECORD_OR_UNION_CODE_P (TREE_CODE (deref_to_type1))
9338 && RECORD_OR_UNION_CODE_P (TREE_CODE (deref_to_type2)))
9339 {
9340 /* [over.ics.rank]
9341
9342 --If class B is derived directly or indirectly from class A
9343 and class C is derived directly or indirectly from B,
9344
9345 --conversion of C* to B* is better than conversion of C* to
9346 A*,
9347
9348 --conversion of B* to A* is better than conversion of C* to
9349 A* */
9350 if (same_type_p (deref_from_type1, deref_from_type2))
9351 {
9352 if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_to_type1,
9353 deref_to_type2))
9354 return 1;
9355 else if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_to_type2,
9356 deref_to_type1))
9357 return -1;
9358 }
9359 else if (same_type_p (deref_to_type1, deref_to_type2))
9360 {
9361 if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_from_type2,
9362 deref_from_type1))
9363 return 1;
9364 else if (is_properly_derived_from (deref_from_type1,
9365 deref_from_type2))
9366 return -1;
9367 }
9368 }
9369 }
9370 else if (CLASS_TYPE_P (non_reference (from_type1))
9371 && same_type_p (from_type1, from_type2))
9372 {
9373 tree from = non_reference (from_type1);
9374
9375 /* [over.ics.rank]
9376
9377 --binding of an expression of type C to a reference of type
9378 B& is better than binding an expression of type C to a
9379 reference of type A&
9380
9381 --conversion of C to B is better than conversion of C to A, */
9382 if (is_properly_derived_from (from, to_type1)
9383 && is_properly_derived_from (from, to_type2))
9384 {
9385 if (is_properly_derived_from (to_type1, to_type2))
9386 return 1;
9387 else if (is_properly_derived_from (to_type2, to_type1))
9388 return -1;
9389 }
9390 }
9391 else if (CLASS_TYPE_P (non_reference (to_type1))
9392 && same_type_p (to_type1, to_type2))
9393 {
9394 tree to = non_reference (to_type1);
9395
9396 /* [over.ics.rank]
9397
9398 --binding of an expression of type B to a reference of type
9399 A& is better than binding an expression of type C to a
9400 reference of type A&,
9401
9402 --conversion of B to A is better than conversion of C to A */
9403 if (is_properly_derived_from (from_type1, to)
9404 && is_properly_derived_from (from_type2, to))
9405 {
9406 if (is_properly_derived_from (from_type2, from_type1))
9407 return 1;
9408 else if (is_properly_derived_from (from_type1, from_type2))
9409 return -1;
9410 }
9411 }
9412
9413 /* [over.ics.rank]
9414
9415 --S1 and S2 differ only in their qualification conversion and yield
9416 similar types T1 and T2 (_conv.qual_), respectively, and the cv-
9417 qualification signature of type T1 is a proper subset of the cv-
9418 qualification signature of type T2 */
9419 if (ics1->kind == ck_qual
9420 && ics2->kind == ck_qual
9421 && same_type_p (from_type1, from_type2))
9422 {
9423 int result = comp_cv_qual_signature (to_type1, to_type2);
9424 if (result != 0)
9425 return result;
9426 }
9427
9428 /* [over.ics.rank]
9429
9430 --S1 and S2 are reference bindings (_dcl.init.ref_) and neither refers
9431 to an implicit object parameter of a non-static member function
9432 declared without a ref-qualifier, and either S1 binds an lvalue
9433 reference to an lvalue and S2 binds an rvalue reference or S1 binds an
9434 rvalue reference to an rvalue and S2 binds an lvalue reference (C++0x
9435 draft standard, 13.3.3.2)
9436
9437 --S1 and S2 are reference bindings (_dcl.init.ref_), and the
9438 types to which the references refer are the same type except for
9439 top-level cv-qualifiers, and the type to which the reference
9440 initialized by S2 refers is more cv-qualified than the type to
9441 which the reference initialized by S1 refers.
9442
9443 DR 1328 [over.match.best]: the context is an initialization by
9444 conversion function for direct reference binding (13.3.1.6) of a
9445 reference to function type, the return type of F1 is the same kind of
9446 reference (i.e. lvalue or rvalue) as the reference being initialized,
9447 and the return type of F2 is not. */
9448
9449 if (ref_conv1 && ref_conv2)
9450 {
9451 if (!ref_conv1->this_p && !ref_conv2->this_p
9452 && (ref_conv1->rvaluedness_matches_p
9453 != ref_conv2->rvaluedness_matches_p)
9454 && (same_type_p (ref_conv1->type, ref_conv2->type)
9455 || (TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (ref_conv1->type)
9456 != TYPE_REF_IS_RVALUE (ref_conv2->type))))
9457 {
9458 if (ref_conv1->bad_p
9459 && !same_type_p (TREE_TYPE (ref_conv1->type),
9460 TREE_TYPE (ref_conv2->type)))
9461 /* Don't prefer a bad conversion that drops cv-quals to a bad
9462 conversion with the wrong rvalueness. */
9463 return 0;
9464 return (ref_conv1->rvaluedness_matches_p
9465 - ref_conv2->rvaluedness_matches_p);
9466 }
9467
9468 if (same_type_ignoring_top_level_qualifiers_p (to_type1, to_type2))
9469 {
9470 int q1 = cp_type_quals (TREE_TYPE (ref_conv1->type));
9471 int q2 = cp_type_quals (TREE_TYPE (ref_conv2->type));
9472 if (ref_conv1->bad_p)
9473 {
9474 /* Prefer the one that drops fewer cv-quals. */
9475 tree ftype = next_conversion (ref_conv1)->type;
9476 int fquals = cp_type_quals (ftype);
9477 q1 ^= fquals;
9478 q2 ^= fquals;
9479 }
9480 return comp_cv_qualification (q2, q1);
9481 }
9482 }
9483
9484 /* Neither conversion sequence is better than the other. */
9485 return 0;
9486}
9487
9488/* The source type for this standard conversion sequence. */
9489
9490static tree
9491source_type (conversion *t)
9492{
9493 for (;; t = next_conversion (t))
9494 {
9495 if (t->kind == ck_user
9496 || t->kind == ck_ambig
9497 || t->kind == ck_identity)
9498 return t->type;
9499 }
9500 gcc_unreachable ();
9501}
9502
9503/* Note a warning about preferring WINNER to LOSER. We do this by storing
9504 a pointer to LOSER and re-running joust to produce the warning if WINNER
9505 is actually used. */
9506
9507static void
9508add_warning (struct z_candidate *winner, struct z_candidate *loser)
9509{
9510 candidate_warning *cw = (candidate_warning *)
9511 conversion_obstack_alloc (sizeof (candidate_warning));
9512 cw->loser = loser;
9513 cw->next = winner->warnings;
9514 winner->warnings = cw;
9515}
9516
9517/* Compare two candidates for overloading as described in
9518 [over.match.best]. Return values:
9519
9520 1: cand1 is better than cand2
9521 -1: cand2 is better than cand1
9522 0: cand1 and cand2 are indistinguishable */
9523
9524static int
9525joust (struct z_candidate *cand1, struct z_candidate *cand2, bool warn,
9526 tsubst_flags_t complain)
9527{
9528 int winner = 0;
9529 int off1 = 0, off2 = 0;
9530 size_t i;
9531 size_t len;
9532
9533 /* Candidates that involve bad conversions are always worse than those
9534 that don't. */
9535 if (cand1->viable > cand2->viable)
9536 return 1;
9537 if (cand1->viable < cand2->viable)
9538 return -1;
9539
9540 /* If we have two pseudo-candidates for conversions to the same type,
9541 or two candidates for the same function, arbitrarily pick one. */
9542 if (cand1->fn == cand2->fn
9543 && (IS_TYPE_OR_DECL_P (cand1->fn)))
9544 return 1;
9545
9546 /* Prefer a non-deleted function over an implicitly deleted move
9547 constructor or assignment operator. This differs slightly from the
9548 wording for issue 1402 (which says the move op is ignored by overload
9549 resolution), but this way produces better error messages. */
9550 if (TREE_CODE (cand1->fn) == FUNCTION_DECL
9551 && TREE_CODE (cand2->fn) == FUNCTION_DECL
9552 && DECL_DELETED_FN (cand1->fn) != DECL_DELETED_FN (cand2->fn))
9553 {
9554 if (DECL_DELETED_FN (cand1->fn) && DECL_DEFAULTED_FN (cand1->fn)
9555 && move_fn_p (cand1->fn))
9556 return -1;
9557 if (DECL_DELETED_FN (cand2->fn) && DECL_DEFAULTED_FN (cand2->fn)
9558 && move_fn_p (cand2->fn))
9559 return 1;
9560 }
9561
9562 /* a viable function F1
9563 is defined to be a better function than another viable function F2 if
9564 for all arguments i, ICSi(F1) is not a worse conversion sequence than
9565 ICSi(F2), and then */
9566
9567 /* for some argument j, ICSj(F1) is a better conversion sequence than
9568 ICSj(F2) */
9569
9570 /* For comparing static and non-static member functions, we ignore
9571 the implicit object parameter of the non-static function. The
9572 standard says to pretend that the static function has an object
9573 parm, but that won't work with operator overloading. */
9574 len = cand1->num_convs;
9575 if (len != cand2->num_convs)
9576 {
9577 int static_1 = DECL_STATIC_FUNCTION_P (cand1->fn);
9578 int static_2 = DECL_STATIC_FUNCTION_P (cand2->fn);
9579
9580 if (DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (cand1->fn)
9581 && is_list_ctor (cand1->fn) != is_list_ctor (cand2->fn))
9582 /* We're comparing a near-match list constructor and a near-match
9583 non-list constructor. Just treat them as unordered. */
9584 return 0;
9585
9586 gcc_assert (static_1 != static_2);
9587
9588 if (static_1)
9589 off2 = 1;
9590 else
9591 {
9592 off1 = 1;
9593 --len;
9594 }
9595 }
9596
9597 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
9598 {
9599 conversion *t1 = cand1->convs[i + off1];
9600 conversion *t2 = cand2->convs[i + off2];
9601 int comp = compare_ics (t1, t2);
9602
9603 if (comp != 0)
9604 {
9605 if ((complain & tf_warning)
9606 && warn_sign_promo
9607 && (CONVERSION_RANK (t1) + CONVERSION_RANK (t2)
9608 == cr_std + cr_promotion)
9609 && t1->kind == ck_std
9610 && t2->kind == ck_std
9611 && TREE_CODE (t1->type) == INTEGER_TYPE
9612 && TREE_CODE (t2->type) == INTEGER_TYPE
9613 && (TYPE_PRECISION (t1->type)
9614 == TYPE_PRECISION (t2->type))
9615 && (TYPE_UNSIGNED (next_conversion (t1)->type)
9616 || (TREE_CODE (next_conversion (t1)->type)
9617 == ENUMERAL_TYPE)))
9618 {
9619 tree type = next_conversion (t1)->type;
9620 tree type1, type2;
9621 struct z_candidate *w, *l;
9622 if (comp > 0)
9623 type1 = t1->type, type2 = t2->type,
9624 w = cand1, l = cand2;
9625 else
9626 type1 = t2->type, type2 = t1->type,
9627 w = cand2, l = cand1;
9628
9629 if (warn)
9630 {
9631 warning (OPT_Wsign_promo, "passing %qT chooses %qT over %qT",
9632 type, type1, type2);
9633 warning (OPT_Wsign_promo, " in call to %qD", w->fn);
9634 }
9635 else
9636 add_warning (w, l);
9637 }
9638
9639 if (winner && comp != winner)
9640 {
9641 winner = 0;
9642 goto tweak;
9643 }
9644 winner = comp;
9645 }
9646 }
9647
9648 /* warn about confusing overload resolution for user-defined conversions,
9649 either between a constructor and a conversion op, or between two
9650 conversion ops. */
9651 if ((complain & tf_warning)
9652 && winner && warn_conversion && cand1->second_conv
9653 && (!DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (cand1->fn) || !DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (cand2->fn))
9654 && winner != compare_ics (cand1->second_conv, cand2->second_conv))
9655 {
9656 struct z_candidate *w, *l;
9657 bool give_warning = false;
9658
9659 if (winner == 1)
9660 w = cand1, l = cand2;
9661 else
9662 w = cand2, l = cand1;
9663
9664 /* We don't want to complain about `X::operator T1 ()'
9665 beating `X::operator T2 () const', when T2 is a no less
9666 cv-qualified version of T1. */
9667 if (DECL_CONTEXT (w->fn) == DECL_CONTEXT (l->fn)
9668 && !DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (w->fn) && !DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (l->fn))
9669 {
9670 tree t = TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (l->fn));
9671 tree f = TREE_TYPE (TREE_TYPE (w->fn));
9672
9673 if (TREE_CODE (t) == TREE_CODE (f) && POINTER_TYPE_P (t))
9674 {
9675 t = TREE_TYPE (t);
9676 f = TREE_TYPE (f);
9677 }
9678 if (!comp_ptr_ttypes (t, f))
9679 give_warning = true;
9680 }
9681 else
9682 give_warning = true;
9683
9684 if (!give_warning)
9685 /*NOP*/;
9686 else if (warn)
9687 {
9688 tree source = source_type (w->convs[0]);
9689 if (! DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (w->fn))
9690 source = TREE_TYPE (source);
9691 if (warning (OPT_Wconversion, "choosing %qD over %qD", w->fn, l->fn)
9692 && warning (OPT_Wconversion, " for conversion from %qT to %qT",
9693 source, w->second_conv->type))
9694 {
9695 inform (input_location, " because conversion sequence for the argument is better");
9696 }
9697 }
9698 else
9699 add_warning (w, l);
9700 }
9701
9702 if (winner)
9703 return winner;
9704
9705 /* DR 495 moved this tiebreaker above the template ones. */
9706 /* or, if not that,
9707 the context is an initialization by user-defined conversion (see
9708 _dcl.init_ and _over.match.user_) and the standard conversion
9709 sequence from the return type of F1 to the destination type (i.e.,
9710 the type of the entity being initialized) is a better conversion
9711 sequence than the standard conversion sequence from the return type
9712 of F2 to the destination type. */
9713
9714 if (cand1->second_conv)
9715 {
9716 winner = compare_ics (cand1->second_conv, cand2->second_conv);
9717 if (winner)
9718 return winner;
9719 }
9720
9721 /* or, if not that,
9722 F1 is a non-template function and F2 is a template function
9723 specialization. */
9724
9725 if (!cand1->template_decl && cand2->template_decl)
9726 return 1;
9727 else if (cand1->template_decl && !cand2->template_decl)
9728 return -1;
9729
9730 /* or, if not that,
9731 F1 and F2 are template functions and the function template for F1 is
9732 more specialized than the template for F2 according to the partial
9733 ordering rules. */
9734
9735 if (cand1->template_decl && cand2->template_decl)
9736 {
9737 winner = more_specialized_fn
9738 (TI_TEMPLATE (cand1->template_decl),
9739 TI_TEMPLATE (cand2->template_decl),
9740 /* [temp.func.order]: The presence of unused ellipsis and default
9741 arguments has no effect on the partial ordering of function
9742 templates. add_function_candidate() will not have
9743 counted the "this" argument for constructors. */
9744 cand1->num_convs + DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (cand1->fn));
9745 if (winner)
9746 return winner;
9747 }
9748
9749 // C++ Concepts
9750 // or, if not that, F1 is more constrained than F2.
9751 if (flag_concepts && DECL_P (cand1->fn) && DECL_P (cand2->fn))
9752 {
9753 winner = more_constrained (cand1->fn, cand2->fn);
9754 if (winner)
9755 return winner;
9756 }
9757
9758 /* F1 is generated from a deduction-guide (13.3.1.8) and F2 is not */
9759 if (deduction_guide_p (cand1->fn))
9760 {
9761 gcc_assert (deduction_guide_p (cand2->fn));
9762 /* We distinguish between candidates from an explicit deduction guide and
9763 candidates built from a constructor based on DECL_ARTIFICIAL. */
9764 int art1 = DECL_ARTIFICIAL (cand1->fn);
9765 int art2 = DECL_ARTIFICIAL (cand2->fn);
9766 if (art1 != art2)
9767 return art2 - art1;
9768
9769 if (art1)
9770 {
9771 /* Prefer the special copy guide over a declared copy/move
9772 constructor. */
9773 if (copy_guide_p (cand1->fn))
9774 return 1;
9775 if (copy_guide_p (cand2->fn))
9776 return -1;
9777
9778 /* Prefer a candidate generated from a non-template constructor. */
9779 int tg1 = template_guide_p (cand1->fn);
9780 int tg2 = template_guide_p (cand2->fn);
9781 if (tg1 != tg2)
9782 return tg2 - tg1;
9783 }
9784 }
9785
9786 /* F1 is a member of a class D, F2 is a member of a base class B of D, and
9787 for all arguments the corresponding parameters of F1 and F2 have the same
9788 type (CWG 2273/2277). */
9789 if (DECL_P (cand1->fn) && DECL_CLASS_SCOPE_P (cand1->fn)
9790 && !DECL_CONV_FN_P (cand1->fn)
9791 && DECL_P (cand2->fn) && DECL_CLASS_SCOPE_P (cand2->fn)
9792 && !DECL_CONV_FN_P (cand2->fn))
9793 {
9794 tree base1 = DECL_CONTEXT (strip_inheriting_ctors (cand1->fn));
9795 tree base2 = DECL_CONTEXT (strip_inheriting_ctors (cand2->fn));
9796
9797 bool used1 = false;
9798 bool used2 = false;
9799 if (base1 == base2)
9800 /* No difference. */;
9801 else if (DERIVED_FROM_P (base1, base2))
9802 used1 = true;
9803 else if (DERIVED_FROM_P (base2, base1))
9804 used2 = true;
9805
9806 if (int diff = used2 - used1)
9807 {
9808 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
9809 {
9810 conversion *t1 = cand1->convs[i + off1];
9811 conversion *t2 = cand2->convs[i + off2];
9812 if (!same_type_p (t1->type, t2->type))
9813 break;
9814 }
9815 if (i == len)
9816 return diff;
9817 }
9818 }
9819
9820 /* Check whether we can discard a builtin candidate, either because we
9821 have two identical ones or matching builtin and non-builtin candidates.
9822
9823 (Pedantically in the latter case the builtin which matched the user
9824 function should not be added to the overload set, but we spot it here.
9825
9826 [over.match.oper]
9827 ... the builtin candidates include ...
9828 - do not have the same parameter type list as any non-template
9829 non-member candidate. */
9830
9831 if (identifier_p (cand1->fn) || identifier_p (cand2->fn))
9832 {
9833 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
9834 if (!same_type_p (cand1->convs[i]->type,
9835 cand2->convs[i]->type))
9836 break;
9837 if (i == cand1->num_convs)
9838 {
9839 if (cand1->fn == cand2->fn)
9840 /* Two built-in candidates; arbitrarily pick one. */
9841 return 1;
9842 else if (identifier_p (cand1->fn))
9843 /* cand1 is built-in; prefer cand2. */
9844 return -1;
9845 else
9846 /* cand2 is built-in; prefer cand1. */
9847 return 1;
9848 }
9849 }
9850
9851 /* For candidates of a multi-versioned function, make the version with
9852 the highest priority win. This version will be checked for dispatching
9853 first. If this version can be inlined into the caller, the front-end
9854 will simply make a direct call to this function. */
9855
9856 if (TREE_CODE (cand1->fn) == FUNCTION_DECL
9857 && DECL_FUNCTION_VERSIONED (cand1->fn)
9858 && TREE_CODE (cand2->fn) == FUNCTION_DECL
9859 && DECL_FUNCTION_VERSIONED (cand2->fn))
9860 {
9861 tree f1 = TREE_TYPE (cand1->fn);
9862 tree f2 = TREE_TYPE (cand2->fn);
9863 tree p1 = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (f1);
9864 tree p2 = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (f2);
9865
9866 /* Check if cand1->fn and cand2->fn are versions of the same function. It
9867 is possible that cand1->fn and cand2->fn are function versions but of
9868 different functions. Check types to see if they are versions of the same
9869 function. */
9870 if (compparms (p1, p2)
9871 && same_type_p (TREE_TYPE (f1), TREE_TYPE (f2)))
9872 {
9873 /* Always make the version with the higher priority, more
9874 specialized, win. */
9875 gcc_assert (targetm.compare_version_priority);
9876 if (targetm.compare_version_priority (cand1->fn, cand2->fn) >= 0)
9877 return 1;
9878 else
9879 return -1;
9880 }
9881 }
9882
9883 /* If the two function declarations represent the same function (this can
9884 happen with declarations in multiple scopes and arg-dependent lookup),
9885 arbitrarily choose one. But first make sure the default args we're
9886 using match. */
9887 if (DECL_P (cand1->fn) && DECL_P (cand2->fn)
9888 && equal_functions (cand1->fn, cand2->fn))
9889 {
9890 tree parms1 = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (TREE_TYPE (cand1->fn));
9891 tree parms2 = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (TREE_TYPE (cand2->fn));
9892
9893 gcc_assert (!DECL_CONSTRUCTOR_P (cand1->fn));
9894
9895 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
9896 {
9897 /* Don't crash if the fn is variadic. */
9898 if (!parms1)
9899 break;
9900 parms1 = TREE_CHAIN (parms1);
9901 parms2 = TREE_CHAIN (parms2);
9902 }
9903
9904 if (off1)
9905 parms1 = TREE_CHAIN (parms1);
9906 else if (off2)
9907 parms2 = TREE_CHAIN (parms2);
9908
9909 for (; parms1; ++i)
9910 {
9911 if (!cp_tree_equal (TREE_PURPOSE (parms1),
9912 TREE_PURPOSE (parms2)))
9913 {
9914 if (warn)
9915 {
9916 if (complain & tf_error)
9917 {
9918 if (permerror (input_location,
9919 "default argument mismatch in "
9920 "overload resolution"))
9921 {
9922 inform (DECL_SOURCE_LOCATION (cand1->fn),
9923 " candidate 1: %q#F", cand1->fn);
9924 inform (DECL_SOURCE_LOCATION (cand2->fn),
9925 " candidate 2: %q#F", cand2->fn);
9926 }
9927 }
9928 else
9929 return 0;
9930 }
9931 else
9932 add_warning (cand1, cand2);
9933 break;
9934 }
9935 parms1 = TREE_CHAIN (parms1);
9936 parms2 = TREE_CHAIN (parms2);
9937 }
9938
9939 return 1;
9940 }
9941
9942tweak:
9943
9944 /* Extension: If the worst conversion for one candidate is worse than the
9945 worst conversion for the other, take the first. */
9946 if (!pedantic && (complain & tf_warning_or_error))
9947 {
9948 conversion_rank rank1 = cr_identity, rank2 = cr_identity;
9949 struct z_candidate *w = 0, *l = 0;
9950
9951 for (i = 0; i < len; ++i)
9952 {
9953 if (CONVERSION_RANK (cand1->convs[i+off1]) > rank1)
9954 rank1 = CONVERSION_RANK (cand1->convs[i+off1]);
9955 if (CONVERSION_RANK (cand2->convs[i + off2]) > rank2)
9956 rank2 = CONVERSION_RANK (cand2->convs[i + off2]);
9957 }
9958 if (rank1 < rank2)
9959 winner = 1, w = cand1, l = cand2;
9960 if (rank1 > rank2)
9961 winner = -1, w = cand2, l = cand1;
9962 if (winner)
9963 {
9964 /* Don't choose a deleted function over ambiguity. */
9965 if (DECL_P (w->fn) && DECL_DELETED_FN (w->fn))
9966 return 0;
9967 if (warn)
9968 {
9969 pedwarn (input_location, 0,
9970 "ISO C++ says that these are ambiguous, even "
9971 "though the worst conversion for the first is better than "
9972 "the worst conversion for the second:");
9973 print_z_candidate (input_location, _("candidate 1:"), w);
9974 print_z_candidate (input_location, _("candidate 2:"), l);
9975 }
9976 else
9977 add_warning (w, l);
9978 return winner;
9979 }
9980 }
9981
9982 gcc_assert (!winner);
9983 return 0;
9984}
9985
9986/* Given a list of candidates for overloading, find the best one, if any.
